'''Deutsche Bank AG''' ({{IPA-de|ˈdɔʏtʃə ˈbaŋk ʔaːˈɡeː|listen|GT Deutsche Bank AG.ogg}}), sometimes referred to simply as '''Deutsche''', or internally as '''DB''', is a German multinational [[Investment banking|investment bank]] <!-- Its investment banking arm is a separate institution to its financial services. They are separate components that add up to the diversified services of the company. Leave as "investment bank and financial services company". --> and [[financial services]] company headquartered in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt, Germany]], and dual-listed on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] and the [[New York Stock Exchange]]. 

Deutsche Bank was founded in 1870 in [[Berlin]]. From 1929 to 1937, following its merger with [[Disconto-Gesellschaft]], it was known as '''''Deutsche Bank und Disconto-Gesellschaft''''' or DeDi-Bank.<ref name=Balderston>{{citation |title=German Banking between the Wars: The Crisis of the Credit Banks |author=Theo Balderston |journal=Business History Review |date=1991 |volume=65 |issue=3 |pages=554–605 |publisher=Harvard College |doi=10.2307/3116768 |jstor=3116768 |s2cid=154642962  }}</ref>{{rp|580}} Other transformative acquisitions have included those of [[Mendelssohn & Co.]] in 1938, [[Morgan, Grenfell & Company|Morgan Grenfell]] in 1990, [[Bankers Trust]] in 1998,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Acquisition of Bankers Trust Successfully Closed |url=http://www.deutsche-bank.de/ir/en/index.html?contentOverload=http://www.deutsche-bank.de/ir/en/releases_766.shtml&loadFlash=/ir/en/1613.html |access-date=17 August 2011 |publisher=Deutsche-bank.de}}</ref> and [[Deutsche Postbank]] in 2010.

As of 2018, the bank's network spanned 58 countries with a large presence in Europe, the Americas, and Asia.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Deutsche Bank |title=Deutsche Bank Location Finder |url=https://www.db.com/company/en/location-finder.htm?kid=lf.inter-en.redirect |access-date=26 May 2018 |website=Deutsche Bank |archive-date=26 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526112925/https://www.db.com/company/en/location-finder.htm?kid=lf.inter-en.redirect }}</ref> It is a component of the [[DAX]] stock market index and is often referred to as the [[List of banks in Germany|largest German banking institution]], with Deutsche Bank holding the majority stake in [[DWS Group]] for combined assets of 2.2 trillion euros, rivaling even [[Sparkassen-Finanzgruppe]] in terms of combined assets. 

Deutsche Bank has been designated a global [[Systemically important financial institution|systemically important bank]] by the [[Financial Stability Board]] since 2011.<ref name=":6">{{Cite magazine |date=23 September 2020 |title=The FinCEN Files Shed New Light on a Scandalous Episode at Deutsche Bank |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-fincen-files-shed-new-light-on-a-scandalous-episode-at-deutsche-bank |access-date=2 March 2022 |magazine=The New Yorker |language=en-US}}</ref> It has been designated as a Significant Institution since the entry into force of [[European Banking Supervision]] in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the [[European Central Bank]].<ref>{{cite web |website=European Central Bank |title=The list of significant supervised entities and the list of less significant institutions |url=https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm-listofsupervisedentities1409en.pdf |date=4 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |website=European Central Bank |title=List of supervised entities |date=1 January 2023 |url=https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.listofsupervisedentities202302.en.pdf }}</ref>

According to a 2020 article in the ''New Yorker'', Deutsche Bank had long had an "abject" reputation among major banks, as it has been involved in major scandals across various issue areas.<ref name=":6">{{Cite magazine |date=23 September 2020 |title=The FinCEN Files Shed New Light on a Scandalous Episode at Deutsche Bank |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-fincen-files-shed-new-light-on-a-scandalous-episode-at-deutsche-bank |access-date=2 March 2022 |magazine=The New Yorker |language=en-US}}</ref>

==History==
{{multiple image| align=right| total_width=300
| image1=Adelbert Delbrück.jpg
| image2=Ludwig Bamberger.jpg
| footer = Adelbert Delbrück (left) and Ludwig Bamberger (right) are often referred to as the key founders of Deutsche Bank<ref name=DBH>{{citation |title=Deutsche Bank from 1870 until today: Rooted in Germany – global from the beginning |publisher=Deutsche Bank |url=https://www.db.com/files/documents/Deutsche-Bank-History--Chronicle-from-1870-until-today.pdf |year=2018}}</ref>{{rp|2}}}}
[[File:Deutsche Bank 1881.jpg|thumb|Share of the Deutsche Bank, issued 2 November 1881]]
[[File:Berlin, Mitte, Mauerstrasse 25-28, Deutsche Bank, Block II, 1909.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Former Deutsche Bank headquarters|de|Gebäudekomplex der Deutschen Bank}} on Mauerstrasse 25-28 in [[Berlin]], photographed in 1909]]
[[File:Berlin, Mitte, Mauerstrasse 25-28, Deutsche Bank, Block II.jpg|thumb|The same building in 2010, following partial rebuilding after World War II]]
[[File:Berlin, Mitte, Mauerstrasse 29-32, Deutsche Bank-Komplex, Block I.jpg|thumb|Another view of Deutsche Bank's former head office complex, corner of Mauerstrasse and Französische Strasse]]

===1870–1933===

Deutsche Bank was founded in 1870 in [[Berlin]] as a specialist bank for financing foreign trade and promoting German exports.<ref name="FP">{{Cite web |last=James |first=Harold |title=Deutsche Bank Isn't Deutsch Anymore |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/02/24/deutsche-bank-uber-alles/ |access-date=20 November 2018 |website=Foreign Policy |date=24 February 2016 |language=en}}</ref> It subsequently played a large part in developing Germany's financial services industry, as its business model focused on providing finance to industrial customers.<ref name="FP" /> The bank's statute was adopted on 22 January 1870, and on 10 March 1870 the [[Prussia]]n government granted it a banking license. The statute laid great stress on foreign business: {{blockquote|The object of the company is to transact banking business of all kinds, in particular, to promote and facilitate trade relations between Germany, other European countries and overseas markets.<ref>Statut der Deutschen Bank Aktien-Gesellschaft, Berlin 1870, pp.&nbsp;3–4.</ref>|sign=|source=}} Prior to the founding of Deutsche Bank, German importers and exporters were dependent upon British and French banking institutions in the world markets—a serious handicap in that German [[Bill of exchange|bills]] were almost unknown in international commerce, generally disliked and subject to a higher rate of a discount than English or French bills.<ref name="ea">{{Americana|wstitle=Deutsche Bank, The|inline=1}}</ref>

The founding members were: Hermann Zwicker (Bankhaus Gebr. Schickler, Berlin); Anton Adelssen (Bankhaus Adelssen & Co., Berlin); [[Adelbert Delbrück]] (Bankhaus Delbrück, Leo & Co.); Heinrich von Hardt (Hardt & Co., Berlin, New York); [[Ludwig Bamberger]] (politician, former chairman of Bischoffsheim, Goldschmidt & Co); Victor Freiherr von Magnus (Bankhaus F. Mart Magnus); {{Interlanguage link|Adolph vom Rath|de}} (Bankhaus Deichmann & Co., Cologne); Gustav Kutter (Bankhaus Gebrüder Sulzbach, Frankfurt); and Gustav Müller (Württembergische Vereinsbank, Stuttgart). The First directors were Wilhelm Platenius, [[Georg von Siemens|Georg Siemens]], and [[Hermann Wallich]].{{cn|date=December 2023}} Georg Siemens was a son of a cousin of [[Werner von Siemens]].<ref name="H James" />  The bank initially operated from the first floor of a building at 21 Französische Strasse, then in 1871 moved to premises near the [[Berlin Stock Exchange]], and in 1876 started building its massive head office complex on Mauerstrasse.{{R|DBH|p=3}}

The bank's first domestic branches, inaugurated in 1871 and 1872, were opened in [[Bremen]]<ref>{{citation |author=Manfred Pohl & Angelika Raab-Rebentisch |title=Die Deutsche Bank in Bremen 1871–1996 |location=Munich |publisher=Zurich (Piper) |year=1996}}</ref> and [[Hamburg]].<ref>{{citation |author=Manfred Pohl & Angelika Raab-Rebentisch |title=Die Deutsche Bank in Hamburg 1872–1997 |location=Munich |publisher=Zurich (Piper) |year=1996}}</ref> Its first overseas offices opened in [[Shanghai]] and [[Yokohama]] in 1872, and London in 1873,{{R|DBH|p=2}} followed by South American offices between 1874 and 1886.<ref name="H James">{{Cite book |last=James |first=H |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gArOx8n77JIC&q=Deutsche+Bank |title=The Nazi Dictatorship and the Deutsche Bank |date=13 September 2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-83874-6 |access-date=11 July 2012}}</ref> The branch opening in London, after one failure and another partially successful attempt, was a prime necessity for the establishment of credit for the German trade in what was then the world's money center.<ref name=ea/> Deutsche Bank also took advantage of the [[Panic of 1873]] by taking over a number of banks in liquidation, including the Berlin-based {{lang|de|Deutsche Union}} which had itself consolidated a number of failed banks in the early 1870s.<ref name=Whale>{{citation |url=https://socialsciences.mcmaster.ca/econ/ugcm/3ll3/whale/JointStockBankingGermany.pdf |title=Joint Stock Banking in Germany: A Study of the German Creditbanks Before and After the War |author=P. Barrett Whale |year=1930}}</ref>{{rp|18}}

Major projects in the early years of the bank included the [[Northern Pacific Railroad]] in the US<ref>{{citation |author=Christopher Kobrak |title=Banking on Global Markets. Deutsche Bank and the United States, 1870 to the Present |location=New York |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2008}}</ref> and the [[Baghdad Railway]] (1888).<ref>{{citation |title=A Century of Deutsche Bank in Turkey |url=https://country.db.com/turkey/documents/Centenary-book.pdf?language_id=1 |year=2008 |publisher=Deutsche Bank}}</ref>{{rp|21–27}} In Germany, the bank was instrumental in the financing of bond offerings of steel company [[Krupp]] (1879) and introduced the chemical company [[Bayer]] to the Berlin stock market.

The second half of the 1890s saw the beginning of a new period of expansion at Deutsche Bank. The bank formed alliances with large regional banks, giving itself an entry into Germany's main industrial regions. It thus formed community-of-interests partnerships with {{ill|Bergisch-Märkische Bank|de}} in [[Elberfeld]] and {{ill|Schlesischer Bankverein|de}} in [[Breslau]], linked to the fast-growing industrial economies of the [[Rhineland]] and [[Silesia]] respectively;{{R|NMC|p=473}} it eventually acquired the two banks in 1914 and 1917 respectively.{{R|DBH|p=4}} Joint ventures were symptomatic of the concentration then under way in the German banking industry. For Deutsche Bank, domestic branches of its own were still something of a rarity at the time; the Frankfurt branch<ref>Historische Gesellschaft der Deutschen Bank (ed.), Die Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt am Main, Munich, Zurich (Piper) 2005.</ref> dated from 1886 and the Munich branch from 1892, while further branches were established in Dresden and Leipzig<ref>Manfred Pohl / Angelika Raab-Rebentisch, Die Deutsche Bank in Leipzig 1901–2001, Munich, Zurich (Piper) 2001.</ref> in 1901.

In 1889, Deutsche Bank participated in the creation of the [[Deutsch-Asiatische Bank]] in [[Shanghai]], in 1894, of the [[Banca Commerciale Italiana]] in [[Milan]], and in 1898, of the [[Banque Internationale de Bruxelles]].{{R|NMC|p=436}}

In addition, the bank rapidly perceived the value of specialist institutions for the promotion of foreign business. Gentle pressure from the Foreign Ministry played a part in the establishment of Deutsche Ueberseeische Bank<ref>Manfred Pohl, Deutsche Bank Buenos Aires 1887–1987, Mainz (v. Hase & Koehler) 1987.</ref> in 1886 and the stake taken in the newly established Deutsch-Asiatische Bank<ref>Maximilian Müller-Jabusch, 50 Jahre Deutsch-Asiatische Bank 1890–1939, Berlin 1940.</ref> three years later, but the success of those companies showed that their existence made sound commercial sense. By end-1908, Deutsche was by far the largest German joint-stock bank by total deposits, with a total of 489 million Marks ahead of [[Dresdner Bank]] (225 million), [[Disconto-Gesellschaft]] (219 million), [[Darmstädter Bank]] (109 million) and [[A. Schaaffhausen'scher Bankverein]] (72 million).<ref name=NMC>{{citation |title=The German Great Banks and Their Concentration in connection with The Economic Development of Germany |url=https://historyofeconomicthought.mcmaster.ca/riesser/GreatGermanBanks.pdf |year=1911 |author=Jacob Riesser |publisher=National Monetary Commission |location=Washington DC}}</ref>{{rp|209}} At that time, Deutsche Bank was referred to as one of the four "D-Banks" (all of which had names starting with a D) that dominated German commercial banking, together with Darmstädter Bank, Disconto-Gesellschaft, and Dresdner Bank.<ref name=HandbookDE>{{citation |url=https://cgsc.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/api/collection/p4013coll8/id/2634/download |title=Army Service Forces Manual M356-5 / Military Government Handbook – Germany – Section 5: Money and Banking |publisher=U.S. Army Service Forces |location=Washington DC |author=Federal Reserve Board |date=March 1945}}</ref>{{rp|13}}

[[File:Kredietbank Brussels.jpg|thumb|Office building erected 1912 by Deutsche Bank for its branch in [[Brussels]], expropriated following [[World War I]], later head office of [[Kredietbank]]<ref>{{cite web |website=Région de Bruxelles-Capitale, Inventaire du Patrimoine Architectural |title=Le Stuart |url=https://monument.heritage.brussels/fr/buildings/33437}}</ref>]]
[[File:Deutsche Bank und Disconto-Gesellschaft 1932.jpg|thumb|Share of the Deutsche Bank und Disconto-Gesellschaft, issued March 1932]]

During [[World War I]] and in its immediate aftermath, the operations of Deutsche Bank in Brussels, London, Tokyo and Yokohama were expropriated; conversely, its activity in the [[Ottoman Empire]] expanded considerably,{{cn|date=December 2023}} and it greatly expanded its footprint in Germany.{{R|DBH|p=5}} In 1919, the bank purchased the state's share of Universum Film Aktiengesellschaft ([[UFA GmbH|UFA]]).<ref name=":3">{{Cite book |last1=Plumpe |first1=Werner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UIfQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT299 |title=Deutsche Bank: The Global Hausbank, 1870 – 2020 |last2=Nützenadel |first2=Alexander |last3=Schenk |first3=Catherine |date=5 March 2020 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-4729-7730-4 |page=299 |language=en}}</ref> In 1926, the bank assisted in the merger of Daimler and Benz.<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite book |last1=Whittington |first1=Richard |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TnqH2fxnRlcC&pg=PA97 |title=The European Corporation: Strategy, Structure, and Social Science |last2=Mayer |first2=Michael |date=2002 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-925104-9 |page=97 |language=en}}</ref>

The bank merged with [[Disconto-Gesellschaft]] in 1929 and rebranded itself [[Deutsche Bank und Disconto-Gesellschaft]], sometimes referred to as DeDi-Bank.<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 September 1929 |title=TWO LEADING BANKS COMBINE IN BERLIN; Deutsche and Disconto Gesellschaft Form Biggest of Kind in German History. 285,000,000-MARK CAPITAL Combined Deposits 4,000,000,000----Believed Forerunner of Other Financial Consolidations. Announcement of Merger. One Employed 14,000 Persons. |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/09/27/archives/two-leading-banks-combine-in-berlin-deutsche-and-disconto.html |access-date=17 April 2020 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 1930, Deutsche Bank & Disconto-Gesellschaft maintained a similar dominant position as before World War I, with 4.8 billion Reichsmarks in total deposits ahead of [[Danat-Bank]] (2.4 billion), Dresdner Bank (2.3 billion), [[Commerz- und Privatbank]] (1.5 billion), [[Reichs-Kredit-Gesellschaft]] (619 million), and [[Berliner Handels-Gesellschaft]] (412 million).{{R|Whale|p=354}}

In the [[European banking crisis of 1931|crisis summer of 1931]] the [[Deutsche Golddiskontbank]], a subsidiary of the [[Reichsbank]], acquired 35 percent of DeDi-Bank's equity as part of a sector-wide rescue,{{R|Balderston|p=597}} bringing total government ownership of the bank to 38.5 percent. This did not, however, result in significant government interference in the management of the company, unlike at Dresdner Bank whose capital was near-completely nationalized.<ref name=Bel>{{citation |title=Against the mainstream: Nazi privatization in 1930s Germany |author=Germà Bel |journal=Economic History Review |issue=1 |date=February 2010 |volume=63 |pages=34–55 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-0289.2009.00473.x |jstor=27771569 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27771569}}</ref>{{rp|7}}

===1933–1945===

When [[Adolf Hitler]] became leader of Germany, Deutsche Bank increasingly became integrated into the Nazi power structures, and fully implemented the Nazi policy of [[Aryanization (Nazism)|aryanization]]. In 1934 it dismissed its three [[Jewish]] management board members, [[Oscar Wassermann]], Theodor Frank, and [[Georg Solmssen]]; in 1938 it dismissed its last Jewish supervisory board member. By the end of 1938, it had been involved as an intermediary and lender in at least 363 cases of expropriation of Jewish-owned businesses.{{R|DBH|p=6}} In 1938, it acquired Jewish-controlled German bank [[Mendelssohn & Co.]] under duress.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Feuer |first=Alan |date=18 December 2007 |title=A Lawsuit Will Determine the Fate of 2 Picassos |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/18/nyregion/18picasso.html |access-date=1 October 2020 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last1=Plumpe |first1=Werner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UIfQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT352 |title=Deutsche Bank: The Global Hausbank, 1870 – 2020 |last2=Nützenadel |first2=Alexander |last3=Schenk |first3=Catherine |date=5 March 2020 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-4729-7730-4 |page=352 |language=en}}</ref> Meanwhile, the Nazi government fully re-privatized Deutsche Bank in 1935-1937, largely out of budgetary considerations.{{R|Bel|p=7}} Its name changed back to Deutsche Bank in 1937.<ref>{{Cite news |date=9 September 1937 |title=Deutsche Bank Resumes Name |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1937/09/09/archives/deutsche-bank-resumes-name.html |access-date=17 April 2020 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

While the Nazi policies of [[financial repression]] were largely unhelpful to the domestic business of Deutsche and other German commercial banks, its expansionary behavior created opportunities that Deutsche Bank pursued. In 1938 following Hitler's [[Anschluss]] of [[Austria]], Deutsche Bank gradually took control of [[Creditanstalt-Bankverein]], the former country's leading bank. On {{date|1938/03/26}} the latter was coerced to enter a "friendship agreement" with Deutsche Bank, by which the latter secured a presence in its board of directors.<ref name=UC4/> Creditanstalt executive [[Louis Nathaniel de Rothschild|Louis de Rothschild]] was immediately arrested and imprisoned, deprived of his position and property, then released upon payment of $21,000,000, believed to have been the largest bail bond in history for any individual,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Baron Louis De Rothschild Dead: Paid $21,000,000 Ransom to Nazis {{!}} Jewish Telegraphic Agency|url=https://www.jta.org/1955/01/17/archive/baron-louis-de-rothschild-dead-paid-21000000-ransom-to-nazis|access-date=2018-10-26|website=www.jta.org|date=20 March 2015 |language=en-US}}</ref> and migrated to the U.S. in 1939 after more than one year in custody. Later in 1938, Creditanstalt was jointly taken over, without compensation, by German government holding {{ill|VIAG (conglomerate)|lt=VIAG|de|VIAG}}, Deutsche Bank,<ref>{{cite book |last=MacDonogh |first=G |title=1938: Hitler's Gamble |url=https://archive.org/details/hitlersgamble00macd |url-access=limited |location=New York |publisher=Basic Books |year=2009 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/hitlersgamble00macd/page/n60 49], 69|isbn=9780465009541 }}</ref> and the [[Reichsbank]], which held respectively 51 percent, 25 percent, and 12 percent of its capital.{{R|rehab|p=5}}<ref name=UC4/> In April 1942, Deutsche Bank raised its ownership to 51 percent by acquiring a block of shares from VIAG.<ref name=UC4>{{cite web |website=Bank Austria |title=Überblick 1938-1945 |url=https://www.bankaustria.at/geschichte/ueberblick-1938-1945.jsp }}</ref> During wartime, the Creditanstalt expanded its operations into Nazi-occupied Czechoslovakia, Poland, Yugoslavia,<ref name=WHW_Creditanstalt>{{cite web |website=Wien Geschichte Wiki |title=Creditanstalt-Bankverein |url=https://www.geschichtewiki.wien.gv.at/Creditanstalt-Bankverein }}</ref> and in Nazi-allied Bulgaria.<ref name=rehab>{{citation |title=The Rehabilitation of Austria 1945-1947, Volume III |author=U.S. Allied Commission Austria |url=https://cgsc.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/api/collection/p4013coll8/id/1880/download |date=1947}}</ref>{{rp|5}}

In September 1938, following the [[Munich Agreement]], Deutsche Bank took over the branches of Prague-based {{ill|Böhmische Union Bank|de}} (BUB) in the [[Sudetenland]]. In March 1939, it forcibly took over control of the BUB itself, in which it built a majority stake complemented with prior shareholding of Creditanstalt. It also took over management control of the [[National Bank of Greece]] during the [[Axis occupation of Greece]], without however acquiring ownership out of consideration for Italian sensitivities.<ref>{{cite book |title=Occupied Economies: An Economic History of Nazi-Occupied Europe, 1939-1945 |url=https://dokumen.pub/occupied-economies-an-economic-history-of-nazi-occupied-europe-1939-1945-1845204824-9781845204822-o-4627421.html |author=Hein A.M. Klemann & Sergei Kudryashov |publisher=Berg |year=2012}}</ref> Through the Creditanstalt-Bankverein, Deutsche Bank also became a major shareholder of the {{lang|de|Allgemeiner Jugoslawischer Bankverein}} (AJB), which had been formed in 1928 from the two former branches of the [[Wiener Bankverein]] in Belgrade and Zagreb, and of the [[Landesbank für Bosnien und Herzegowina]] in [[Sarajevo]], together with the [[Société Générale de Belgique]] and its affiliate [[Banque Belge pour l'Étranger]].{{R|HandbookYU|p=49}} In 1940, following the [[German invasion of Belgium (1940)|German invasion of Belgium]], Deutsche Bank bought out the Belgian stake under duress and became the AJB's dominant shareholder, with 88 percent held either directly or through Creditanstalt.{{R|Aleksic|p=242}} Deutsche Bank simultaneously took control of the Landesbank in Sarajevo.{{R|HandbookYU|p=49}} Following the German [[invasion of Yugoslavia]], the AJB was divided into two separate institutions, respectively the {{lang|de|Bankverein AG Belgrad}} in [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|occupied Serbia]],<ref name=HandbookYU>{{citation |title=Army Service Forces Manual M355-5 / Civil Affairs Handbook Yugoslavia: Money and Banking |publisher=U.S. Army Service Forces |location=Washington DC |author=Federal Reserve Board |date=February 1944 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1l7niteyT8C&q=%22Jugoslavenska+udru%C5%BEena+banka%22+anglo }}</ref>{{rp|xiii}} and the {{lang|de|Bankverein für Kroatien AG}} in the [[Independent State of Croatia]].{{R|Aleksic|p=331}} Both these banks' assets were eventually confiscated by the newly established Communist authorities in October 1944, and they were subsequently liquidated.<ref name=Aleksic>{{citation |author=Vesna Aleksić |title=From affiliation to nazification: The political destiny of a 'Grossbank' in Yugoslavia 1818-1945 |publisher= Institute of Economic Sciences |location=Belgrade |date=2021 |url=https://www.academia.edu/46933114 }}</ref>{{rp|394}}

During the war, Deutsche Bank provided banking facilities for the [[Gestapo]] and, through its branch in [[Katowice]], loaned the funds used to build the [[Auschwitz]] camp and the nearby [[IG Farben]] facilities. Deutsche Bank publicly acknowledged its involvement at Auschwitz in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schmid |first=John |date=5 February 1999 |title=Deutsche Bank Linked To Auschwitz Funding |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/05/news/05iht-berlin.t.html |access-date=28 January 2010}}</ref> It also was a principal participant in the Nazi regime's gold transactions. Between 1942 and 1944, Deutsche Bank purchased 4,446 kg of gold from the Reichsbank, of which 744 kg came from [[Holocaust]] victims.{{R|DBH|p=7}}

In an effort to come to terms with its past during the Nazi era, Deutsche Bank in 1995 published a history volume that detailed its entanglement with the dictatorship.<ref>{{cite book |author=Lothar Gall, Gerald D. Feldman, Harold James, Carl-Ludwig Holtfrerich, and Hans E. Büschgen |title=Die Deutsche Bank 1870-1995 |location=Munich |publisher=C.H. Beck |year=1995}}</ref> In December 1999, along with other major German companies, Deutsche Bank contributed to a US$5.2&nbsp;billion compensation fund following lawsuits brought by Holocaust survivors;<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 December 2004 |title=$5.2 Billion German Settlement |url=http://treasurer.ca.gov/holocaust/germanbank.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908070905/http://www.treasurer.ca.gov/holocaust/germanbank.htm |archive-date=8 September 2006 |access-date=17 August 2011}}</ref><ref>For a detailed account of Deutsche Bank's involvement with the Nazis see: Harold James. ''The Nazi Dictatorship and the Deutsche Bank.'' Cambridge University Press, 2004, 296 pp., {{ISBN|0-521-83874-6}}.</ref> U.S. officials had reportedly threatened to block Deutsche Bank's $10&nbsp;billion purchase of Bankers Trust if it did not contribute to the fund.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Holocaust claims threaten bank merger|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/276309.stm|access-date=23 January 2021|website=BBC News}}</ref>

===1945–2000===
[[File:Frankfurt Roßmarkt Deutsche Bank.jpg|thumb|Former Disconto-Gesellschaft branch building in [[Frankfurt]] on the {{ill|Roßmarkt (Frankfurt am Main){{!}}Roßmarkt|de|Roßmarkt (Frankfurt am Main)}} (erected 1904), which served as head office of Deutsche Bank's Hesse unit from 1947 to 1952, of {{lang|de|Süddeutsche Bank}} from 1952 to 1957, then of Deutsche Bank itself from 1957 to 1984]]
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-14492-0004, Berlin, Potsdamer Platz, Neubau, Bank.jpg|thumb|Head office of Disconto-Bank, Deutsche Bank's Berlin unit, designed by {{ill|Paul Schwebes|de}}; completed 1951 and photographed in 1952]]
[[File:Berlin potsdamer strasse bülowstrasse 26.07.2012 13-12-07.jpg|thumb|The same building (Potsdamer Straße 140, after upwards expansion in 1955-1957) in 2012, repurposed as {{lang|de|Finanzamt Schöneberg}} and still hosting a branch of Deutsche Bank]]
[[File:Deutsche-Bank-Otto-Suhr-Allee-Berlin-Charlottenburg-06-2017b.jpg|thumb|Highrise of the Deutsche Bank in Berlin, designed by Friedrich Koch and {{interlanguage link|Günter Hönow|de}}, 1966-1968]]

Following Germany's defeat in [[World War II]], the Allied authorities, in 1948, ordered Deutsche Bank's break-up into regional banks.<ref name=":5">{{Cite book |last1=Lange |first1=Even |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qUmoDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT370 |title=Centres and Peripheries in Banking: The Historical Development of Financial Markets |last2=Olsson |first2=Ulf |last3=Fraser |first3=Iain L. |date=5 December 2016 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-95293-4 |pages=370–71 |language=en}}</ref> These regional banks were later consolidated into three major banks in 1952: Norddeutsche Bank AG; Süddeutsche Bank AG; and Rheinisch-Westfälische Bank AG.<ref name=":5" /> In 1957, these three banks merged to form Deutsche Bank AG with its headquarters in Frankfurt.<ref name=":5" />

In 1959, the bank entered retail banking by introducing small personal loans. In the 1970s, the bank pushed ahead with international expansion, opening new offices in new locations, such as [[Milan]] (1977), [[Moscow]], [[London]], [[Paris]], and [[Tokyo]]. In the 1980s, this continued when the bank paid U$603&nbsp;million in 1986 to acquire [[Banca d'America e d'Italia]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=February 2018 |title=La bella banca |url=http://www.bankgeschichte.de/en/docs/Historische_Rundschau-38-engl-Web.pdf |website=Bankgeschichte.de |access-date=20 November 2018 |archive-date=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017203117/http://www.bankgeschichte.de/en/docs/Historische_Rundschau-38-engl-Web.pdf }}</ref>

In 1972, the bank established its ''Fiduciary Services Division'' which provides support to its [[Wealth management|private wealth division]].<ref name=PrivateWealthManBrochure>{{cite web |url=http://www.pwm.db.com/080403_FSD_Brochure.pdf |title=Private Wealth Management. Deutsche Bank: A passion to perform. Fiduciary Solutions |work=Deutsche Bank website |date=March 2008 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=18 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130418065426/http://www.pwm.db.com/080403_FSD_Brochure.pdf}}</ref>

At 8:30 am on 30 November 1989, [[Alfred Herrhausen]], chairman of Deutsche Bank, was killed when a car that he was in exploded while he was traveling in the [[Frankfurt]] suburb of [[Bad Homburg]]. The [[Red Army Faction]] claimed responsibility for the blast.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boehmer |first=George |url=https://apnews.com/article/8e59e745748a723ef3e3c6be84d236c7 |title=West Germany's Most Powerful Banker Killed In Bomb Blast |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=30 November 1989 |access-date=2 July 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Belton |first=Catherine |author-link=Catherine Belton |url=https://www.politico.com/news/magazine/2020/06/20/vladimir-putin-dresden-kgb-330203 |title=Did Vladimir Putin Support Anti-Western Terrorists as a Young KGB Officer? Putin has sworn his time as a KGB officer in Dresden was uneventful. There's a lot of reason to doubt that claim. |work=[[Politico]] |date=20 June 2020 |access-date=2 July 2021}}</ref>

In 1989, the first steps towards creating a significant investment-banking presence were taken with the acquisition of [[Morgan, Grenfell & Co.]], a UK-based investment bank which was renamed Deutsche Morgan Grenfell in 1994. In 1995 to greatly expand into international investments and money management, Deutsche Bank hired Edson Mitchell, a risk specialist from [[Merrill Lynch]], who hired two other former Merrill Lynch risk specialists Anshu Jain and William S. Broeksmit.<ref name="nytimes.com">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/30/business/dealbook/deutsche-bank-flew-and-fell-some-paid-a-high-price.html|title=Deutsche Bank Flew and Fell. Some Paid a High Price.|first=Landon Thomas|last=Jr|work=The New York Times |date=30 December 2016|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> By the mid-1990s, the buildup of a capital-markets operation had got underway with the arrival of a number of high-profile figures from major competitors. Ten years after the acquisition of Morgan Grenfell, the US firm [[Bankers Trust]] was added. Bankers Trust suffered losses during the [[1998 Russian financial crisis]] since it had a large position in Russian government bonds,<ref name="Forbes2007-10-30">{{Cite news |last=Moyer |first=Liz |date=30 October 2007 |title=Super-Size That Severance |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/10/30/merrill-severance-compensation-biz-wall-cx_lm_1031failure.html |access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> but avoided financial collapse by being acquired by Deutsche Bank for $10&nbsp;billion in November 1998.<ref name=Giant>{{Cite news |last=Andrews |first=Edmund L. |author-link=Edmund L. Andrews |date=1 December 1998 |title=Bank Giant: The Overview; Deutsche Gets Bankers Trust for $10 Billion |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/01/business/bank-giant-the-overview-deutsche-gets-bankers-trust-for-10-billion.html?pagewanted=all |access-date=12 December 2018}}</ref> On 4 June 1999, Deutsche Bank merged its Deutsche Morgan Grenfell and Bankers Trust to became Deutsche Asset Management (DAM) with Robert Smith as the CEO.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/361454.stm Morgan Grenfell bites the dust] BBC News, 4 June 1999.</ref> This made Deutsche Bank the fourth-largest money management firm in the world after [[UBS]], [[Fidelity Investments]], and the Japanese post office's life insurance fund.<ref name=Giant/> At the time, Deutsche Bank owned a 12% stake in [[DaimlerChrysler]] but United States banking laws prohibit banks from owning industrial companies, so Deutsche Bank received an exception to this prohibition through 1978 legislation from Congress.<ref name=Giant/>

Deutsche continued to build up its presence in Italy with the acquisition in 1993 of [[Banca Popolare di Lecco]] from [[Banca Popolare di Novara]] for about $476&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |agency=Reuters |date=27 November 1993 |title=Company News; Deutsche Bank Announces Big Expansion in Italy |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/27/business/company-news-deutsche-bank-announces-big-expansion-in-italy.html |access-date=31 October 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1999, it acquired a minority interest in [[Cassa di Risparmio di Asti]].

===21st century===

In the [[September 11 attacks|11 September 2001 terrorist attacks]] the [[Deutsche Bank Building]] in [[Lower Manhattan]], formerly Bankers Trust Plaza, was heavily damaged by the collapse of the South Tower of the World Trade Center.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 May 2014 |title=The Deutsche Bank building: Tombstone at Ground Zero – Mar. 20, 2008 |url=https://money.cnn.com/2008/03/19/news/companies/ground_zero.fortune/?postversion=2008032004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005224/https://money.cnn.com/2008/03/19/news/companies/ground_zero.fortune/?postversion=2008032004 |archive-date=2 May 2014 |access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref> Demolition work on the 39-story building continued for nearly a decade, and was completed in early 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 March 2011 |title=Lower Manhattan: 130 Liberty Street |url=http://www.lowermanhattan.info/construction/project_updates/130_liberty_street__77170.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110328045518/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/construction/project_updates/130_liberty_street__77170.aspx |archive-date=28 March 2011 |access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>

In October 2001, Deutsche Bank was listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]]. This was the first NYSE listing after interruption due to [[11 September attacks]]. The following year, Josef Ackermann became CEO of Deutsche Bank and served as CEO until 2012 when he became involved with the [[Bank of Cyprus]].<ref name="IBT2014-11-11">{{Cite news |last=Brinded |first=Lianna |date=11 November 2014 |title=Bank of Cyprus Funded and Controlled by Ex-KGB, Billionaires and Controversial Former Financiers |work=International Business Times UK |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bank-cyprus-funded-controlled-by-ex-kgb-billionaires-former-rbs-deutsche-bank-financiers-1474198 |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812205910/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/bank-cyprus-funded-controlled-by-ex-kgb-billionaires-former-rbs-deutsche-bank-financiers-1474198 |archive-date=12 August 2015}}</ref><ref name="NYT2017-07-19">{{Cite news |last1=Protess |first1=Ben |last2=Silver-Greenberg |first2=Jessica |last3=Drucker |first3=Jesse |date=19 July 2017 |title=Big German Bank, Key to Trump's Finances, Faces New Scrutiny |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/big-german-bank-key-to-trumps-finances-faces-new-scrutiny.html |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720003726/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/19/business/big-german-bank-key-to-trumps-finances-faces-new-scrutiny.html |archive-date=20 July 2017}}</ref> Then, beginning in 2002, Deutsche Bank strengthened its U.S. presence when it purchased Scudder Investments.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scudder PIC joins Deutsche Bank's private banking |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2002/06/24/daily10.html |access-date=31 October 2019 |website=bizjournals.com}}</ref> Meanwhile, in Europe, Deutsche Bank increased its private-banking business by acquiring Rued Blass & Cie (2002) and the Russian investment bank United Financial Group (2005) founded by the United States banker Charles Ryan and the Russian official [[Boris Fyodorov]] which followed [[Anshu Jain]]'s aggressive expansion to gain strong relationships with state partners in Russia.<ref name="Newsweek2017-12-21">{{Cite news |last=Harding |first=Luke |author-link=Luke Harding |date=21 December 2017 |title=Is Donald Trump's Dark Russian Secret Hiding in Deutsche Bank's Vaults? |work=[[Newsweek]] |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2017/12/29/donald-trump-russia-secret-deutsche-bank-753780.html |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109121942/https://www.newsweek.com/2017/12/29/donald-trump-russia-secret-deutsche-bank-753780.html |archive-date=9 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="Independent2017-04-14">{{Cite news |last=Sampathkumar |first=Mythili |date=14 April 2017 |title=Former MI6 chief Richard Dearlove says Donald Trump borrowed money from Russia during 2008 financial crisis: Days before taking office, Mr Trump said Russia had never had any 'levarage' over him |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/richard-dearlove-mi6-trump-russia-money-2008-financial-crisis-us-election-a7684341.html |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214234725/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/richard-dearlove-mi6-trump-russia-money-2008-financial-crisis-us-election-a7684341.html |archive-date=14 December 2018}}</ref> Jain persuaded Ryan to remain with Deutsche Bank at its new Russian offices and later, in April 2007, sent the president and chairman of the management board of [[VTB|VTB Bank]] [[Andrey Kostin]]'s son Andrey to Deutsche Bank's Moscow office.<ref name=Newsweek2017-12-21/><ref name="Izvestia2011-07-02">{{Cite news |date=2 July 2011 |title=Сын главы ВТБ Андрей Костин разбился на квадроцикле: 32-летний банкир погиб на отдыхе в Ярославской области |language=ru |trans-title=The son of the head of VTB Andrei Kostin crashed on a quad: 32-year-old banker died on holiday in the Yaroslavl region |work=[[Izvestia]] |url=https://iz.ru/news/493519 |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717212858/https://iz.ru/news/493519 |archive-date=17 July 2018}}</ref>{{efn|Andrey Kostin (1979–2011), a Russian banker and son of [[Andrey Kostin]] who is the president and chairman of the management board of [[VTB|VTB Bank]], graduated from the [[Financial University under the Government of the Russian Federation|Russian Government Finance Academy]] in 2000 and began working with Deutsche Bank's London office in 2000.<ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> From 2002 to 2007, the younger Andrey Kostin worked in Deutsche Bank's Office of Interbank and Corporate Sales in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe, the Middle East and Africa.<ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> In April 2007, Anshu Jain sent the younger Andrey Kostin to work at Deutsche Bank's Moscow office.<ref name=Newsweek2017-12-21/><ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> While he was at Deutsche Bank's Moscow office, the Moscow office began posting profits of $500&nbsp;million to $1&nbsp;billion a year.<ref name=Newsweek2017-12-21/><ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> He served on its management board beginning July 2008 and was the deputy chairman of the management board from February 2011.<ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> On 2 July 2011, at 7:30&nbsp;am, while he was at a vacation retreat reserved for [[Federal Security Service|FSB]] personnel, he died when his Can-Am Outlander-800 ATV crashed into a tree along a country road near [[Pereslavl-Zalessky]] and the village of Los ({{lang-ru|Лось}}) in the [[Yaroslavl Oblast|Yaroslavl region]] of Russia.<ref name=Izvestia2011-07-02/> He was not wearing a helmet.<ref name="Gazeta2011-07-04">{{Cite news |last1=Шипилов |first1=Евгений |last2=Танас |first2=Ольга |date=4 July 2011 |title=Погиб на трезвую голову: В ДТП погиб сын президента ВТБ Андрей Костин |language=ru |trans-title=Killed sober: The accident killed the son of the president of VTB Andrei Kostin |work=[[Gazeta.ru|Gazeta]] |url=https://www.gazeta.ru/auto/2011/07/04_a_3684801.shtml |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018082655/https://www.gazeta.ru/auto/2011/07/04_a_3684801.shtml |archive-date=18 October 2018}}</ref>}} Later, in 2008, to establish [[VTB Capital]], numerous bankers from Deutsche Bank's Moscow office were hired by VTB Capital.<ref name=NYT2017-07-19/><ref name="BloombergBusinessWeek2011-12-22">{{Cite news |last=Corcoran |first=Jason |date=22 December 2011 |title=Putin Pushing Russian Banks Points 'Two Tanks' at Western Firms |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |location=London |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-12-22/putin-pushing-russian-banks-points-two-tanks-at-western-firms.html/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307031258/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-12-22/putin-pushing-russian-banks-points-two-tanks-at-western-firms.html|archive-date=7 March 2012}}</ref><ref name="Forbes2011-10-12">{{Cite news |last=Rapoza |first=Kenneth |date=12 October 2011 |title=Russian Bank Heads To New York |work=[[Forbes]] |location=New York City |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2011/10/12/russian-bank-heads-to-new-york/ |url-status=live |access-date=17 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015202147/http://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2011/10/12/russian-bank-heads-to-new-york |archive-date=15 October 2011 }}</ref> In Germany, further acquisitions of [[Norisbank]], Berliner Bank and [[Deutsche Postbank]] strengthened Deutsche Bank's retail offering in its home market. This series of acquisitions was closely aligned with the bank's strategy of bolt-on acquisitions in preference to so-called "transformational" mergers. These formed part of an overall growth strategy that also targeted a sustainable 25% [[return on equity]], something the bank achieved in 2005.{{Citation needed|date=January 2021}}

On 1 October 2003, Deutsche Bank and [[Dresdner Bank]] entered into a payment transaction agreement with [[Deutsche Postbank|Postbank]] to have Postbank process payments as the [[Clearing house (finance)|clearing center]] for the three banks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.globalcustodian.com/deutsche-bank-and-dresdner-bank-outsource-payments-processing-to-postbank/ |title=Deutsche Bank And Dresdner Bank Outsource Payments Processing To Postbank. Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank have agreed to have their payments processed by Postbank. Preliminary agreements for this have now been signed by the three companies. The three banks say they see this as an important step in implementing their strategic objectives |work=[[Global Custodian]] website |date=1 October 2003 |access-date=13 February 2021}}</ref>

Since the mid-1990s Deutsche Bank commercial real estate division offered [[Donald Trump]] financial backing, even though in the early 1990s [[Citibank]], [[Manufacturers Hanover]], [[Chemical Bank|Chemical]], [[Bankers Trust]], and 68 other entities refused to financially support him.<ref name=Newsweek2017-12-21/><ref name=Independent2017-04-14/><ref name="FinancialTimes2017-09-30">{{Cite news |last1=McLannahan |first1=Ben |last2=Scannell |first2=Kara |last3=Silverman |first3=Gary |date=30 August 2017 |title=Donald Trump's debt to Deutsche Bank |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/8c6d9dca-882c-11e7-bf50-e1c239b45787 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/8c6d9dca-882c-11e7-bf50-e1c239b45787 |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |access-date=29 June 2018}}</ref>{{efn|Justin Kennedy, son of [[Anthony Kennedy]], and others such as Jon Vaccaro, Mike Offit, Steve Stuart, Eric Schwartz, and Tobin "Toby" Cobb are central to Donald Trump's financial support at Deutsche Bank.<ref name=FinancialTimes2017-09-30/>  Justin Kennedy worked for Deutsche Bank from 1997 to 2009 becoming the global head of real estate capital markets.<ref name=NYT2017-07-19/><ref name="NYT2018-06-28">{{Cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Liptak |first2=Adam |date=28 June 2018 |title=Inside the White House's Quiet Campaign to Create a Supreme Court Opening |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/28/us/politics/trump-anthony-kennedy-retirement.html |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref>}}

In 2008, Trump sued Deutsche Bank for $3&nbsp;billion and a few years later, he shifted his financial portfolio from the investment banking division to Deutsche Bank [[Wealth management|private wealth division]] with [[Rosemary Vrablic]], formerly of [[Citigroup]], [[Bank of America]], and [[Merrill Lynch]], becoming Trump's new personal banker at Deutsche Bank.<ref name=NYT2017-07-19/><ref name="Guardian2017-02-16">{{Cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Luke |author-link=Luke Harding |last2=Kirchgaessner |first2=Stephanie |last3=Hopkins |first3=Nick |last4=Smith |first4=David |date=16 February 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank examined Donald Trump's account for Russia links |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/feb/16/deutsche-bank-examined-trump-account-for-russia-links |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="CommercialObserver2013-02-16">{{Cite news |last=Gaines |first=carl |date=6 February 2013 |title=Deutsche Bank's Rosemary Vrablic and Private Banking's Link to CRE Finance |work=[[Commercial Observer]] |url=https://commercialobserver.com/2013/02/deutsche-banks-rosemary-vrablic-and-private-bankings-link-to-cre-finance/ |access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/18/business/trump-deutsche-bank.html|title=A Mar-a-Lago Weekend and an Act of God: Trump's History With Deutsche Bank|first=David|last=Enrich|work=The New York Times |date=18 March 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>{{efn|Because of Deutsche Bank's global presence and strong support from attorneys in the [[United States]] and elsewhere, the Fiduciary Services Division, especially at the Singapore branch of Deutsche Bank, and closely associated one stop service provider companies including Atlas Corporate Services, Commonwealth Trust Limited (CTL), and the Portcullis TrustNet Group which was established in the 1980s gives support to private wealth management by establishing structures in critical places in the world such as trusts in [[Crown dependencies|Crown possessions]] including [[Guernsey]], [[Isle of Man]], [[Jersey]]; limited liability companies (LLC) in [[United Kingdom]], [[Delaware]], etc.; foundations in [[Liechtenstein]]; holding companies in [[Delaware]], [[Bahamas]], [[Cayman Islands]], [[British Virgin Islands]], [[Belize]], [[Nevis]], [[Seychelles]], [[Mauritius]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[New Zealand]], [[Cook Islands]], [[Samoa]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[Panama]], [[Ireland]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Luxembourg]], [[Monaco]], [[Cyprus]], [[Gibraltar]], etc.; discrete bank accounts in [[Panama]], [[Bahamas]], [[Switzerland]], [[Latvia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Beijing]], etc.<ref name=PrivateWealthManBrochure/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gürtler |first1=Lena |last2=Fuchs |first2=Mareike |last3=Heinzle |first3=Christoph |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks171.html |title=Steueroasen: Deutsche Bank besonders aktiv |trans-title=Tax havens: Deutsche Bank is particularly active |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=5 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=9 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409031558/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks171.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gürtler |first1=Lena |last2=Fuchs |first2=Mareike |last3=Heinzle |first3=Christoph |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks131.html |title=Steueroasen: Deutsche Bank in der Kritik |trans-title=Tax havens: Deutsche Bank under fire |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=4 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=7 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407060125/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks131.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=David |last2=Frayman |first2=Harold |last3=Ball |first3=James |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2012/nov/25/offshore-secrets-revealed-shadowy-side |title=Offshore secrets revealed: the shadowy side of a booming industry: A worldwide research effort in collaboration with BBC Panorama and the ICIJ reveals the people behind these anonymous companies |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 November 2012 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=20 April 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130420150036/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2012/nov/25/offshore-secrets-revealed-shadowy-side}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Strunz |first=Benedikt |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks129.html |title=CTL: Spezialisten für Steueroasen |trans-title=CTL: specialists in tax havens |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=4 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=7 April 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130407042904/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks129.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Strunz |first=Benedikt |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks127.html |title=Am Fiskus vorbei mit Portcullis TrustNet |trans-title=Passing the tax authorities with Portcullis TrustNet |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=4 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=7 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407042900/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks127.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portcullis-trustnet.com/en/about_us/about_group/ |title=About Portcullis TrustNet Group of Companies |work=Portcullis TrustNet website |date=January 2010 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=16 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116183518/http://www.portcullis-trustnet.com/en/about_us/about_group/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Strunz |first=Benedikt |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks185.html |title=Offshore: Rundum sorglos ins Steuerparadies |trans-title=Offshore: all-round carefree to the tax haven |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=5 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=9 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409031501/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks185.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Heinzle |first1=Christoph |last2=Guertler |first2=Lena |last3=Fuchs |first3=Mareike |last4=Brinkmann |first4=Bastian |last5=Giesen |first5=Christoph |url=http://www.icij.org/offshore/deutsche-bank-helped-customers-maintain-hundreds-offshore-entities |title= Secrecy for Sale: Inside the Global Offshore Money Maze. Deutsche Bank Helped Customers Maintain Hundreds of Offshore Entities |work=[[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]] (ICIJ) |date=4 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=8 October 2015 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20151008052329/http://www.icij.org/offshore/deutsche-bank-helped-customers-maintain-hundreds-offshore-entities}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks193.html |title="Offshore-Leaks"-Karte: Enthüllungen weltweit |trans-title=Offshore Leaks Map: Revelations Worldwide |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=9 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=9 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409035204/https://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks193.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks101.html |title="Offshore-Leaks": Steueroasen und Strohmänner |trans-title="Offshore Leaks": tax havens and straw men |language=de |work=[[:de:Norddeutscher Rundfunk#Online|NDR.de]] |date=29 April 2013 |access-date=10 February 2021 |archive-date=29 April 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130429080201/http://www.ndr.de/home/offshoreleaks101.html}}</ref>}}

In 2007, the company's headquarters, the [[Deutsche Bank Twin Towers]] building, was extensively renovated for three years, certified [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum and DGNB Gold.

In 2010, the bank developed and owned the [[Cosmopolitan of Las Vegas]], after the casino's original developer defaulted on its borrowings. Deutsche Bank ran it at a loss until its sale in May 2014. The bank's exposure at the time of sale was more than $4&nbsp;billion, and sold the property to [[Blackstone Group]] for $1.73&nbsp;billion.<ref name="CosmopolitanSale">{{Cite news |title=Unprofitable Vegas casino sold by Deutsche Bank for $1.73&nbsp;billion |publisher=The Las Vegas News.Net |url=http://www.thelasvegasnews.net/index.php/sid/222063703/scat/1e0899715fbc2697/ht/Unprofitable-Vegas-casino-sold-by-Deutsche-Bank-for-173-billion |access-date=17 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517132426/http://www.thelasvegasnews.net/index.php/sid/222063703/scat/1e0899715fbc2697/ht/Unprofitable-Vegas-casino-sold-by-Deutsche-Bank-for-173-billion |archive-date=17 May 2014 }}</ref>

==== Housing credit bubble and CDO market ====

On 3 January 2014, it was reported that Deutsche Bank would settle a lawsuit brought by US shareholders, who had accused the bank of bundling and selling bad real estate loans before the 2008 downturn. This settlement came subsequent and in addition to Deutsche's $1.93&nbsp;billion settlement with the US Housing Finance Agency over similar litigation related to the sale of mortgage-backed securities to [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=3 January 2014 |title=Deutsche Bank Settles with US Shareholders | work=[[MarketWatch]] |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/deutsche-bank-settles-with-us-shareholders-2014-01-03}}</ref>

==== Leveraged super-senior trades ====
Former employees including Eric Ben-Artzi and Matthew Simpson have claimed that, during the crisis, Deutsche failed to recognize up to $12 billion of paper losses on its $130 billion portfolio of leveraged [[Senior debt#Super-senior status|super senior]] trades, although the bank rejects the claims.<ref name=hid>{{Cite news |last1=Braithwaite |first1=Tom |last2=Scannell |first2=Kara |last3=Mackenzie |first3=Michael |date=5 December 2012 |title=Deutsche hid up to $12bn losses, say staff |work=Financial Times |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f03eb1d6-3efd-11e2-a095-00144feabdc0.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f03eb1d6-3efd-11e2-a095-00144feabdc0.html |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> A company document of May 2009 described the trades as "the largest risk in the trading book",<ref name=strength>{{Cite news |last1=Braithwaite |first1=Tom |last2=Mackenzie |first2=Michael |last3=Scannell |first3=Kara |date=5 December 2012 |title=Deutsche Bank: Show of strength or a fiction? |work=[[Financial Times]] |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f03eb1d6-3efd-11e2-a095-00144feabdc0 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/f03eb1d6-3efd-11e2-a095-00144feabdc0 |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live}}</ref> and the whistleblowers allege that had the bank accounted properly for its positions its capital would have fallen to the extent that it might have needed a government bailout.<ref name=hid/> One of them claims that "If Lehman Brothers didn't have to mark its books for six months it might still be in business, and if Deutsche had marked its books it might have been in the same position as Lehman."<ref name=strength/>

Deutsche had become the biggest operator in this market, which were a form of credit derivative designed to behave like the most senior tranche of a CDO.<ref name=strength/> Deutsche bought insurance against default by [[Blue chip (stock market)|blue-chip companies]] from investors, mostly Canadian pension funds, who received a stream of insurance premiums as income in return for posting a small amount of collateral.<ref name=strength/> The bank then sold protection to US investors via the CDX [[Credit default swap index|credit index]], the spread between the two was tiny but was worth $270m over the 7 years of the trade.<ref name=strength/> It was considered very unlikely that many blue chips would have problems at the same time, so Deutsche required collateral of just 10% of the contract value.

The risk of Deutsche taking large losses if the collateral was wiped out in a crisis was called the gap option.<ref name=strength/> Ben-Artzi claims that after modeling came up with "economically unfeasible" results, Deutsche accounted for the gap option first with a simple 15% "haircut" on the trades (described as inadequate by another employee in 2006) and then in 2008 by a $1–2bn reserve for the credit correlation desk designed to cover all risks, not just the gap option.<ref name=strength/> In October 2008, it stopped modeling the gap option and just bought S&P put options to guard against further market disruption, but one of the whistleblowers has described this as an inappropriate hedge.<ref name=strength/> A model from Ben-Artzi's previous job at Goldman Sachs suggested that the gap option was worth about 8% of the value of the trades, worth $10.4bn. Simpson claims that traders were not simply understating the gap option but actively [[mismarking]] the value of their trades.<ref name=strength/>

====European debt crisis, 2009–today====
{{Main|European debt crisis}}

In 2008, Deutsche Bank reported its first annual loss in five decades,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Deutsche Bank in line for annual loss |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4f1f0ecc-e21d-11dd-b1dd-0000779fd2ac |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/4f1f0ecc-e21d-11dd-b1dd-0000779fd2ac |archive-date=10 December 2022 |website=[[Financial Times]] |date=14 January 2009 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> despite receiving billions of dollars from its insurance arrangements with [[AIG]], including US$11.8&nbsp;billion from funds provided by US [[taxpayers]] to bail out AIG.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Javers | first=Eamon  |title=AIG ships billions in bailout abroad |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/03/aig-ships-billions-in-bailout-abroad-020039 | work=[[Politico]] |date=15 March 2009 }}</ref>

Based on a preliminary estimation from the [[European Banking Authority]] (EBA), in late 2011, Deutsche Bank AG needed to raise capital of about €3.2&nbsp;billion as part of a required 9% core Tier 1 ratio after sovereign debt write-down starting in mid-2012.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.afr.com/markets/eu-banks-slip-down-a-fire-sale-trail-20111214-i458i | title=EU banks slip down a fire sale trail | first1=Anne-Sylvaine |last1=Chassany | first2=Kevin | last2=Crowley | first3=Charles |last3=Penty | work=[[Australian Financial Review]] | date=14 December 2011}}</ref>

As of 2012, Deutsche Bank had negligible exposure to [[Greece]], but Spain and Italy accounted for a tenth of its European private and corporate banking business with credit risks of about €18&nbsp;billion in Italy and €12&nbsp;billion in Spain.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Böll, Sven |author2=Hawranek, Dietmar |author3=Hesse, Martin |author4=Jung, Alexander |author5=Neubacher, Alexander |author6=Reiermann, Christian |author7=Sauga, Michael |author8=Schult, Christoph |author9=Seith, Anne |translator=Sultan, Christopher |date=25 June 2012 |title=Imagining the Unthinkable. The Disastrous Consequences of a Euro Crash |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/fears-grow-of-consequences-of-potential-euro-collapse-a-840634.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628013301/http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/fears-grow-of-consequences-of-potential-euro-collapse-a-840634-2.html |archive-date=28 June 2012 }}</ref>

In 2017, Deutsche Bank needed to get its common equity tier-1 capital ratio up to 12.5% in 2018 to be marginally above the 12.25% required by regulators.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank reports core capital ratio of 11.9% despite 2016 full year net loss of EUR 1.4 billion – Newsroom |url=https://www.db.com/newsroom_news/2017/medien/deutsche-bank-reports-core-capital-ratio-of-11-9-per-cent-despite-2016-full-year-net-loss-of-eur-1-4-billion-en-11468.htm |access-date=12 October 2021 |website=www.db.com |publication-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>

====Since 2012====
In January 2014, Deutsche Bank reported a €1.2&nbsp;billion ($1.6&nbsp;billion) pre-tax loss for the fourth quarter of 2013. This came after analysts had predicted a profit of nearly €600&nbsp;million, according to FactSet estimates. Revenues slipped by 16% versus the prior year.<ref>{{Cite news |date=19 January 2014 |title=When Deutsche Bank sneaks out its results on a Sunday night, they can't be good |work=Quartz |url=http://qz.com/168536/when-deutsche-bank-sneaks-out-its-results-on-a-sunday-night-they-cant-be-good/#!}}</ref>

Deutsche Bank's Capital Ratio Tier-1 (CET1) was reported in 2015 to be only 11.4%, lower than the 12% median CET1 ratio of Europe's 24 biggest publicly traded banks, so there would be no dividend for 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 October 2015 |title=Deutsche Bank Plans to Eliminate Dividend for Two Years in Overhaul |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-28/deutsche-bank-plans-to-scrap-dividend-for-2-years-in-overhaul}}</ref> Furthermore, 15,000 jobs were to be cut.<ref>{{Cite news |date=29 October 2015 |title=Deutsche Bank cutting 15,000 jobs as new CEO sets out strategy plan |newspaper=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/deutsche-bank-results-idUSL8N12T1KK20151029}}</ref>

In June 2015, the then co-CEOs, [[Jürgen Fitschen]] and Anshu Jain, both offered their resignations<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank appoints John Cryan to succeed Jürgen Fitschen and Anshu Jain |url=https://www.db.com/ir/en/content/ir_releases_2015_4985.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622103011/https://www.db.com/ir/en/content/ir_releases_2015_4985.htm |archive-date=22 June 2015 |access-date=7 June 2015 |publisher=Deutsche Bank }}</ref> to the bank's supervisory board, which were accepted. Jain's resignation took effect in June 2015, but he provided consultancy to the bank until January 2016. Fitschen continued as joint CEO until May 2016. The appointment of [[John Cryan]] as joint CEO was announced, effective July 2015; he became sole CEO at the end of Fitschen's term.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Jain Era Ending as Deutsche Bank Appoints Cryan for Top Job |newspaper=Bloomberg.com |date=7 June 2015 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-07/deutsche-bank-appoints-john-cryan-to-replace-jain-fitschen |access-date=28 March 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>

In January 2016, Deutsche Bank pre-announced a 2015 loss before income taxes of approximately €6.1&nbsp;billion and a net loss of approximately €6.7&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank reports preliminary full year and fourth quarter 2015 results – Newsroom |url=https://www.db.com/newsroom_news/2016/medien/deutsche-bank-reports-preliminary-full-year-and-fourth-quarter-2015-results-en-11368.htm |website=db.com}}</ref> Following this announcement, a bank analyst at [[Citigroup|Citi]] declared: "We believe a capital increase now looks inevitable and see an equity shortfall of up to €7 billion, on the basis that Deutsche may be forced to book another €3 billion to €4 billion of litigation charges in 2016."<ref name="Euromoney">{{Cite news |date=March 2016 |title=Can Cryan halt Deutsche Bank's decline? |work=Euromoney |url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3534126/Can-Cryan-halt-Deutsche-Banks-decline.html}}</ref>

May 2017, Chinese [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[HNA Group]] became its biggest shareholder, owning 9.90% of its shares.<ref>{{Cite news |date=3 May 2017 |title=HNA Group, Secretive Chinese Conglomerate, Takes Top Stake in Deutsche Bank |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/03/business/dealbook/china-hna-group.html}}</ref>
However, HNA Group's stake reduced to 8.8% as of 16 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/correction-hna-cuts-deutsche-bank-stake-again-2018-02-16 |title=Correction: HNA cuts Deutsche Bank stake again |date=16 February 2018 |website=MarketWatch |access-date=10 February 2022}}</ref>

In November 2018, the bank's Frankfurt offices were raided by police in connection with investigations around the [[Panama papers]] and [[money laundering]]. Deutsche Bank released a statement confirming it would "cooperate closely with prosecutors".<ref name="Guardian2018-11-29">{{Cite web |last=Harding |first=Luke |date=29 November 2018 |title=Deutsche Bank offices raided in connection with Panama Papers |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/nov/29/deutsche-bank-offices-raided-connection-with-panama-papers |access-date=29 November 2018 |website=The Guardian}}</ref>

AUTO1 FinTech is a joint venture of AUTO1 Group, Allianz, SoftBank and Deutsche Bank.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Storbeck|first=Olaf|date=22 June 2020|title=Auto1 battles with fintech partner|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e11ea4e6-1375-45bd-9c87-db3d0375429e |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/e11ea4e6-1375-45bd-9c87-db3d0375429e |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription|website=Financial Times}}</ref>

In February 2019, HNA Group announced cutting stake in Deutsche Bank to 6.3 percent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutsche-bank-hna-idUSKCN1Q5079|title=HNA cuts stake in Deutsche Bank to 6.3 percent: SEC filing|date=16 February 2019|website=Reuters|access-date=10 February 2022}}</ref> It was further reduced to 0.19 percent as at March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deraktionaer.de/artikel/fintech-versicherung-banken/deutsche-bank-aufsichtsrat-kauft-anteile-hna-aus-china-ist-draussen-20194439.html|title=Deutsche-Bank-Aufsichtsrat kauft Anteile – HNA aus China ist draußen|date=13 December 2019|website=DER AKTIONÄR|access-date=10 February 2022|language=de}}</ref>

During the Annual General Meeting in May 2019, CEO [[Christian Sewing]] said he was expecting a "deluge of criticism" about the bank's performance and announced that he was ready to make "tough cutbacks"<ref>{{Cite news |date=23 May 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank CEO Signals More Cuts to Investment Bank |work=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/deutsche-bank-ceo-signals-more-cuts-to-investment-bank-11558604013 |access-date=2 July 2019 |quote=... "tough cutbacks" at the troubled lender's investment bank, his strongest public admission yet that the business needs a dramatic overhaul.}}</ref> after the failure of merger negotiations with [[Commerzbank AG]] and weak profitability. According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', "its finances and strategy [are] in disarray and 95 percent of its market value [has been] erased".<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 June 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank, in a Last-Ditch Effort to Stop Its Spiral, Could Lay Off 20,000 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/business/deutsche-bank-cuts-layoffs.html?rref=collection%2Ftimestopic%2FLabor&action=click&contentCollection=timestopics&region=stream&module=stream_unit&version=latest&contentPlacement=4&pgtype=collection |access-date=2 July 2019 |quote=Other investment-banking divisions also could be slashed, including the bond-trading business and teams that specialize in selling and trading various types of derivatives.}}</ref>  News headlines in late June 2019 claimed that the bank would cut 20,000 jobs, over 20% of its staff, in a restructuring plan.<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 June 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Plans to Cut as Many as 20,000 Jobs in Revamp |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-30/deutsche-bank-plans-to-cut-as-many-as-20-000-jobs-in-overhaul |access-date=2 July 2019 |publisher=Bloomberg |quote=The bank expects to make a formal announcement no later than July 8, one person said. The Wall Street Journal first reported on the plan to cut as many as 20,000 jobs.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=1 July 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Discusses Lower Capital Buffer With Regulators |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-01/deutsche-bank-discusses-lowering-capital-buffer-with-regulators |access-date=2 July 2019 |publisher=Bloomberg |quote=...including the loss of as many as 20,000 jobs over the coming years ... The cost could run into the billions of euros, analysts estimate}}</ref> On 8 July 2019, the bank began to cut 18,000 jobs, including entire teams of equity traders in Europe, the US, and Asia. On the previous day, Sewing had laid blame on unnamed predecessors who created a "culture of poor capital allocation" and chasing revenue for the sake of revenue, according to a ''[[Financial Times]]'' report, and promised that going forward, the bank "will only operate where we are competitive".<ref>{{Cite news |date=8 July 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank starts cull of 18,000 jobs |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/65cfe4ec-a144-11e9-974c-ad1c6ab5efd1 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/65cfe4ec-a144-11e9-974c-ad1c6ab5efd1 |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |access-date=8 July 2019 |quote=German lender begins its most radical strategic overhaul in two decades}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Farrell |first1=Sean |last2=Kollewe |first2=Julia |last3=Helmore |first3=Edward |date=8 July 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank starts cutting London jobs with 18,000 at-risk worldwide |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/jul/08/deutsche-bank-jobs-staff-london |website=The Guardian}}</ref>

In January 2020, Deutsche Bank had decided to cut the bonus pool at its investment branch by 30% following restructuring efforts.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 January 2020 |title=Deutsche Bank Cuts Investment Bank Bonuses About 30% |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-17/deutsche-bank-cuts-investment-bank-bonuses-about-30-in-overhaul |website=Bloomberg}}</ref>

In February 2021, it was reported that Deutsche Bank made a profit of €113&nbsp;million ($135.6&nbsp;million) for 2020, the first annual net profit it had posted since 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Hanna Ziady|title=Deutsche Bank just posted its first profit in years|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/02/04/investing/deutsche-bank-profit/index.html|access-date=12 February 2021|website=CNN|date=4 February 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Storbeck|first=Olaf|date=4 February 2021|title=Trading boom propels Deutsche Bank to first profit in 6 years|url=https://www.ft.com/content/098222ba-7701-496 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/098222ba-7701-496 |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|website=Financial Times}}</ref>

In March 2021, Deutsche Bank sold about $4&nbsp;billion of holdings seized in the implosion of [[Archegos Capital Management]] in a private deal.<ref name="fortune.com">{{Cite web|title=Deutsche Bank got itself out of Archegos mess with quick sale|url=https://fortune.com/2021/04/01/how-deutsche-bank-managed-survive-unscathed-from-archegos-meltdown/|access-date=2 April 2021|website=Fortune|language=en}}</ref> The move helped Deutsche Bank emerge unscathed after Archegos defaulted on margin loans used to build up highly leveraged bets on stocks.<ref name="fortune.com"/>

