==Logotype==
In 1972, the bank created the world-known blue logo "Slash in a Square" – designed by [[Anton Stankowski]] and intended to represent growth within a risk-controlled framework.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank Logo: Design and History |url=http://www.famouslogos.net/deutsche-bank-logo/ |access-date=18 August 2011 |archive-date=18 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018004004/http://www.famouslogos.net/deutsche-bank-logo }}</ref>

==Business divisions==
[[File:Deutsche Bank building - Sydney.jpg|thumb|180px|Deutsche Bank, [[Sydney]]]]
The bank's business model rests on three pillars – the Corporate & Investment Bank (CIB), the Private & Commercial Bank and Asset Management (DWS).

===Corporate and Investment Bank (CIB)===
[[File:Deutsche Bank munich.jpg|thumb|A Deutsche Bank retail branch in [[Munich]]]]
The Corporate & Investment Bank (CIB) is Deutsche Bank's capital markets business. The CIB comprises the below six units.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank Corporate & Investment Bank |url=https://www.db.com/company/en/corporate-and-investment-bank.htm |access-date=29 April 2018 |website=db.com}}</ref>

* '''Corporate Finance''' is responsible for advisory and mergers & acquisitions (M&A).
* '''Equities / Fixed Income & Currencies'''. These two units are responsible for sales and trading of securities.
* '''Global Capital Markets''' (GCM) is focused on financing and risk management solutions. It includes debt and equity issuances.
* '''Global Transaction Banking''' (GTB) caters to corporates and financial institutions by providing commercial banking products including cross-border payments, cash management, [[Securities Services]], and international trade finance.
* '''Deutsche Bank Research''' provides analysis of products, markets, and trading strategies.

===Private and Commercial Bank===

* '''Private & Commercial Clients Germany / International''' is the retail bank of Deutsche Bank. In Germany, it operates under two brands – Deutsche Bank and Postbank. Additionally, it has operations in Belgium, Italy, Spain and India. The businesses in Poland and Portugal are in the process of being sold.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 December 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank sells chunk of Polish business to Santander |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a40e508a-e0ad-11e7-8f9f-de1c2175f5ce |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221210/https://www.ft.com/content/a40e508a-e0ad-11e7-8f9f-de1c2175f5ce |archive-date=10 December 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |access-date=29 April 2018 |website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=27 March 2018 |title=Deutsche Bank To Sell Portuguese Private and Commercial Clients Business To Abanca |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/brief-deutsche-bank-to-sell-portuguese-p/brief-deutsche-bank-to-sell-portuguese-private-commercial-clients-business-to-abanca-idUSFWN1R905B |access-date=29 April 2018 |website=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=The Financial |date=28 May 2018 |title=Germany's biggest Private & Commercial Bank is launched |url=https://www.finchannel.com/~finchannel/business/banksandservices/73669-germany-s-biggest-private-commercial-bank-is-launched |access-date=29 May 2018 |website=finchannel.com}}</ref>{{update inline|date=April 2021}}
* '''Wealth Management''' functions as the bank's private banking arm, serving [[high-net-worth individual]]s and families worldwide. The division has a presence in the world's private banking hotspots, including Switzerland, Luxembourg, the Channel Islands, the Cayman Islands and Dubai.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wealth Management – Locations |url=https://deutschewealth.com/content/deutschewealth/en/locations.html |access-date=29 April 2018 |website=Deutsche Bank}}</ref>

===Deutsche Asset Management (DWS)===
Deutsche Bank holds a majority stake in the listed asset manager [[DWS Group]] (formerly Deutsche Asset Management), which was separated from the bank in March 2018.

==Controversies==
Deutsche Bank in general as well as specific employees have frequently figured in controversies and allegations of deceitful behavior or illegal transactions. As of 2016, the bank was involved in some 7,800 legal disputes and calculated €5.4&nbsp;billion as litigation reserves,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank: Neuer Skandal &#124; Börse Aktuell |url=http://boerse.ard.de/aktien/deutsche-bank-zwischen-ramsch-und-skandalen100.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404093959/http://boerse.ard.de/aktien/deutsche-bank-zwischen-ramsch-und-skandalen100.html |archive-date=4 April 2017 |access-date=28 March 2017 |website=Boerse.ARD.de }}</ref> with a further €2.2&nbsp;billion held against other contingent liabilities.<ref name="Euromoney" /> According to the ''New Yorker'', Deutsche Bank has long had an "abject" reputation.<ref name=":6" /> Between 2008 and 2016, Deutsche Bank paid around nine billion dollars in fines and settlements related to wrongdoings across different issue areas.<ref name=":6" /> The [[FinCEN Files|FinCEN file]] leaks documented around $1.3&nbsp;trillion of suspicious transactions through Deutsche Bank between 1999 and 2017.<ref name=":6" /> More than half of all suspicious transactions involving major banks in the FinCEN files leaks involved Deutsche Bank.<ref name=":6" />

===Role in financial crisis of 2007–2008===
{{see also|Financial crisis of 2007–2008}}
In January 2017, Deutsche Bank agreed to a $7.2&nbsp;billion settlement with the [[United States Department of Justice]] over its sale and pooling of toxic mortgage securities in the years leading up to the [[Financial crisis of 2007–2008]].  As part of the agreement, Deutsche Bank was required to pay a civil monetary penalty of $3.1&nbsp;billion and provide $4.1&nbsp;billion in consumer relief, such as loan forgiveness. At the time of the agreement, Deutsche Bank was still facing investigations into the alleged manipulation of foreign exchange rates, suspicious equities trades in Russia, as well as alleged violations of [[United States sanctions against Iran]] and other countries. Since 2012, Deutsche Bank had paid more than €12&nbsp;billion for litigation, including a deal with U.S. mortgage-finance giants [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Freifeld |first=Karen |title=Deutsche Bank agrees to $7.2&nbsp;billion mortgage settlement with U.S. |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutsche-bank-mortgages-settlement-idUSKBN14C041 |access-date=13 January 2017 |website=Reuters|date=23 December 2016 }}</ref>

===Espionage scandal, 2009===
In 2009, the bank admitted it engaged in covert espionage on its critics from 2001 to 2007 directed by its corporate security department, although it characterized the incidents as "isolated".<ref name="WSJ">{{Cite news |last1=Crawford |first1=David |last2=Karnitschnig |first2=Matthew |date=3 August 2009 |title=Bank Spy Scandal Widens |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124925060899599929 |access-date=27 January 2010}}</ref> According to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Deutsche Bank had prepared a list of names of people who it wanted investigated for criticism of the bank, including [[Michael Bohndorf]] (an activist investor in the bank), [[Leo Kirch]] (a former media executive in litigation with the bank), and the Munich law firm of [[Bub Gauweiler & Partner]], which represented Kirch.<ref name=WSJ /> According to  the ''Wall Street Journal'', the bank's legal department was involved in the scheme along with its corporate security department.<ref name=WSJ /> The bank hired [[Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton]] to investigate the incidents on its behalf. The Cleary firm submitted its report, which however was not made public.<ref name=WSJ /> According to ''The Wall Street Journal'', the Cleary firm uncovered a plan by which Deutsche Bank was to infiltrate the Bub Gauweiler firm by having a bank [[Mole (espionage)|mole]] hired as an intern at the Bub Gauweiler firm. The plan was allegedly cancelled after the intern was hired but before she started work.<ref name=WSJ /> [[Peter Gauweiler]], a principal at the targeted law firm, was quoted as saying "I expect the appropriate authorities including state prosecutors and the bank's oversight agencies will conduct a full investigation."<ref name=WSJ />

Deutsche Bank's law firm Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton in Frankfurt<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Deutsche Bank undertakes independent investigation |date=22 May 2009 |publisher=deutsche-bank.de |url=http://www.deutsche-bank.de/presse/en/content/press_releases_2009_4505.htm |access-date=28 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601092546/http://www.deutsche-bank.de/presse/en/content/press_releases_2009_4505.htm |archive-date=1 June 2010 }}</ref> published a report in July 2009 saying,<ref name="press">{{Cite press release |title=Deutsche Bank gives update on inquiries |date=22 July 2009 |publisher=deutsche-bank.de |url=http://www.deutsche-bank.de/presse/en/content/press_releases_2009_4551.htm |access-date=27 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601075226/http://www.deutsche-bank.de/presse/en/content/press_releases_2009_4551.htm |archive-date=1 June 2010 }}</ref> it found no systemic misbehaviour and there was no indication that present members of the management board had been involved in any activity that raises legal issues or has had any knowledge of such activities.<ref name=press/> This was confirmed by the Public Prosecutor's Office in Frankfurt in October 2009.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Press release Public Prosecutor's Office in Frankfurt |date=8 October 2009 |publisher=sta-frankfurt.justiz.hessen.de |url=http://www.sta-frankfurt.justiz.hessen.de/irj/STA_Frankfurt_am_Main_Internet?rid=HMdJ_15/STA_Frankfurt_am_Main_Internet/sub/3e3/3e3300ea-27aa-2421-f012-f31e2389e481,,,11111111-2222-3333-4444-100000005003%26overview=true.htm |access-date=14 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719040252/http://www.sta-frankfurt.justiz.hessen.de/irj/STA_Frankfurt_am_Main_Internet?rid=HMdJ_15%2FSTA_Frankfurt_am_Main_Internet%2Fsub%2F3e3%2F3e3300ea-27aa-2421-f012-f31e2389e481%2C%2C%2C11111111-2222-3333-4444-100000005003&overview=true.htm |archive-date=19 July 2011 }}</ref> BaFin found deficiencies in operations within Deutsche Bank's security unit in Germany but no systemic misconduct.<ref>{{Cite news |date=18 December 2009 |title=Deutsche Bank Probe Finds Individual Misconduct |work=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704238104574601913577800846 |access-date=14 October 2010}}</ref> The bank said it took steps to strengthen controls for the mandating of external service providers by its Corporate Security Department.<ref name=press/>

===Deutsche Bank document release, 2014===
On 26 January 2014, William S. Broeksmit, a risk specialist at Deutsche Bank who was very close to Anshu Jain and hired by Edson Mitchell to spearhead Deutsche Bank's foray into international investments and money management in the 1990s, released numerous Deutsche Bank documents from the New York branch of the Deutsche Bank Trust Company Americas (DBTCA), which Broeksmit's adopted son [[Val Broeksmit]], who is a close friend of [[Moby]], later gave, along with numerous emails, to both [[Welt am Sonntag]] and [[ZDF]], which revealed numerous irregularities including both a $10&nbsp;billion money laundering scheme spearheaded by the Russia branch of Deutsche Bank at Moscow, which the New York State Department of Financial Services fined Deutsche Bank $425&nbsp;million, and derivatives improprieties.<ref>{{Cite news |date=14 May 2017 |title=Was suicide of Deutsche Bank executive linked to Trump and Russia money-laundering? |url=https://www.dailykos.com/story/2017/5/14/1662227/-Was-suicide-of-Deutsche-Bank-executive-linked-to-Trump-and-Russia-money-laundering |access-date=12 October 2021}}[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2017/5/14/1662227/-Was-suicide-of-Deutsche-Bank-executive-linked-to-Trump-and-Russia-money-laundering Was suicide of Deutsche Bank executive linked to Trump and Russia money laundering?]</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Laabs |first=Dirk |date=14 May 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank: Freitod offenbart System des verdrängten Risikos |language=de |work=DIE WELT |url=https://www.welt.de/wirtschaft/article164534406/Um-seine-Leiche-herum-lagen-interne-Dokumente-der-Deutschen-Bank.html |access-date=12 October 2021}}[https://www.welt.de/wirtschaft/article164534406/Um-seine-Leiche-herum-lagen-interne-Dokumente-der-Deutschen-Bank.html Um seine Leiche herum lagen interne Dokumente der Deutschen Bank]</ref><ref name="nytimes.com"/><ref>{{Cite news |last= Ian Spiegelman  |date=27 November 2019 |title=Former Deutsche Bank Exec Connected to Trump Loans Dies by Suicide in Malibu}}[https://www.lamag.com/citythinkblog/deutsche-bank-death/ Former Deutsche Bank Exec Connected to Trump Loans Dies by Suicide in Malibu]</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stuart |first=Gwynedd |date=2 October 2019 |title=How Moby Reportedly Played a Role in an Unfolding Trump-Whistleblower Story |language=en-US |url=https://www.lamag.com/citythinkblog/moby-trump-whistleblower/ |access-date=12 October 2021}}[https://www.lamag.com/citythinkblog/moby-trump-whistleblower/ How Moby Reportedly Played a Role in an Unfolding Trump-Whistleblower Story]</ref><ref name="Me and My Whistle-Blower">{{Cite news |last=Enrich |first=David |date=1 October 2019 |title=Me and My Whistle-Blower |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/01/business/val-broeksmit-deutsche-bank-trump-whistle-blower.html |access-date=12 October 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/01/business/val-broeksmit-deutsche-bank-trump-whistle-blower.html Me and My Whistle-Blower]</ref><ref name="ReferenceA"/>{{efn|Val Broeksmit (b. 1976, [[Ukraine]]) emigrated to [[Chicago]] in 1979 with his parents Alexander and Alla. Later, after his mother divorced his father and married Bill Broeksmit, he was adopted by Broeksmit when he was 9. [[Adam Schiff]] subpoenaed Val Broeksmit for the Broeksmit materials about Deutsche Bank to begin House of Representatives investigations into Trump and Deutsche Bank.<ref name="Me and My Whistle-Blower"/><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Flitter |first1=Emily |last2=Enrich |first2=David |date=15 April 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Is Subpoenaed for Trump Records by House Democrats |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/business/deutsche-bank-trump-finances-congress.html |access-date=12 October 2021 |issn=0362-4331}}Deutsche Bank Is Subpoenaed for Trump Records by House Democrats</ref>}}

===Libor scandal, 2015===
{{see also|Libor scandal}}
On 23 April 2015, Deutsche Bank agreed to a combined US$2.5&nbsp;billion in fines – a US$2.175&nbsp;billion fine by American regulators, and a €227&nbsp;million penalty by British authorities – for its involvement in the [[Libor scandal]] uncovered in June 2012. It was one of several banks colluding to fix interest rates used to price hundreds of trillions of dollars of loans and contracts worldwide, including mortgages and student loans.<ref name="NYTFine" /><ref name="ReutersFine" /> Deutsche Bank also pleaded guilty to wire fraud, acknowledging that at least 29 employees had engaged in illegal activity. It was required to dismiss all employees who were involved with the fraudulent transactions.<ref name=ReutersFine /> However, no individuals were charged with criminal wrongdoing. In a Libor first, Deutsche Bank will be required to install an independent monitor.<ref name="NYTFine">{{Cite news |last1=Protess |first1=Ben |last2=Jack Ewing |date=23 April 2015 |title=Deutsche Bank to Pay $2.5 Billion Fine to Settle Rate-Rigging Case |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/24/business/dealbook/deutsche-bank-settlement-rates.html?ref=dealbook |access-date=23 April 2015}}</ref> Commenting on the fine, Britain's [[Financial Conduct Authority]] director Georgina Philippou said "This case stands out for the seriousness and duration of the breaches&nbsp;...  One division at Deutsche Bank had a culture of generating profits without proper regard to the integrity of the market. This wasn't limited to a few individuals but, on certain desks, it appeared deeply ingrained."<ref name="ReutersFine">{{Cite news |date=23 April 2015 |title=Deutsche Bank fined record $2.5&nbsp;billion in rate rigging inquiry |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-deutschebank-libor-settlement-idUSKBN0NE12U20150423 |access-date=23 April 2015}}</ref> The fine represented a record for interest rate related cases, eclipsing a $1.5&nbsp;billion Libor related fine to UBS, and the then-record $450&nbsp;million fine assessed to Barclays earlier in the case.<ref name=ReutersFine /><ref name=NYTFine /> The size of the fine reflected the breadth of wrongdoing at Deutsche Bank, the bank's poor oversight of traders, and its failure to take action when it uncovered signs of abuse internally.<ref name=NYTFine />

=== U.S. sanctions violations, 2015 ===
On 5 November 2015, Deutsche Bank was ordered to pay US$258&nbsp;million (€237.2&nbsp;million) in penalties imposed by the [[New York State Department of Financial Services]] (NYDFS) and the [[United States Federal Reserve Bank]] after the bank was caught doing business with Burma, Libya, Sudan, Iran, and Syria, which were under [[US sanctions]] at the time. According to the US federal authorities, Deutsche Bank handled 27,200 US dollar clearing transactions valued at more than US$10.86&nbsp;billion (€9.98&nbsp;billion) to help evade US sanctions between early 1999 until 2006 which were done on behalf of Iranian, Libyan, Syrian, Burmese, and Sudanese financial institutions and other entities subject to US sanctions, including entities on the [[Specially Designated Nationals]] by the [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank to pay US$258m for violating US sanctions |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/deutsche-bank-to-pay-us/2239426.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106211442/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/business/deutsche-bank-to-pay-us/2239426.html |archive-date=6 January 2016 |access-date=5 November 2015 |publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=NYDFS Announces Deutsche Bank to Pay $258 Million, Install Independent Monitor, Terminate Employees for Transactions on Behalf of Iran, Syria, Sudan, Other Sanctioned Entities |url=http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511041.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107170649/http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1511041.htm |archive-date=7 November 2015 |access-date=5 November 2015 |publisher=New York State Department of Financial Services }}</ref>

In response to the penalties, the bank will pay US$200&nbsp;million (€184&nbsp;million) to the NYDFS while the rest (US$58&nbsp;million; €53.3&nbsp;million) will go to the [[Federal Reserve]]. In addition to the payment, the bank will install an independent monitor, fire six employees who were involved in the incident, and ban three other employees from any work involving the bank's US-based operations.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank fined $258m for violating US sanctions |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/nov/04/deutsche-bank-us-sanctions-fine |access-date=5 November 2015 |website=The Guardian |date=4 November 2015 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]}}</ref>

===Tax evasion, 2016===
In June 2016 six former employees in Germany were accused of being involved in a major tax fraud deal with CO<sub>2</sub> emission certificates, and most of them were subsequently convicted. It was estimated that the sum of money in the tax evasion scandal might have been as high as €850&nbsp;million. Deutsche Bank itself was not convicted due to an absence of corporate liability laws in Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |date=13 June 2016 |title=Steuerbetrug: Sechs Ex-Mitarbeiter der Deutschen Bank verurteilt |url=http://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/unternehmen/2016-06/steuerbetrug-deutsche-bank-umsatzsteuer-landgericht-frankfurt |access-date=28 March 2017 |website=Die Zeit}}</ref>

===Russian money-laundering operations===
In January 2017, the bank was fined $425&nbsp;million by the [[New York State Department of Financial Services]] (DFS)<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 January 2017 |title=DFS Fines Deutsche Bank $425 Million for Russian Mirror-Trading Scheme |url=http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1701301.htm |access-date=28 March 2017 |website=Dfs.ny.gov |archive-date=16 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216204336/http://www.dfs.ny.gov/about/press/pr1701301.htm }}</ref> and £163&nbsp;million by the UK [[Financial Conduct Authority]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jill Treanor |title=Deutsche Bank fined $630m over Russia money laundering claims &#124; Business |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/jan/31/deutsche-bank-fined-630m-over-russia-money-laundering-claims |access-date=28 March 2017}}</ref> regarding accusations of [[money laundering|laundering]] $10&nbsp;billion out of Russia.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Thomas | first=Landon Jr. |date=30 January 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank Fined for Helping Russians Launder $10 Billion |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/30/business/dealbook/deutsche-bank-fined-for-helping-russians-launder-10-billion.html |access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Wang |first=Christine |date=30 January 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank to pay $425&nbsp;million fine over Russian money-laundering scheme: New York regulator |publisher=CNBC |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/30/deutsche-bank-to-pay-425-million-fine-over-russian-money-laundering.html |access-date=30 January 2017 |archive-date=31 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131001021/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/30/deutsche-bank-to-pay-425-million-fine-over-russian-money-laundering.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=30 January 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank Ends N.Y. Mirror-Trade Probe for $425 Million |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-30/deutsche-bank-settles-n-y-mirror-trade-probe-for-425-million |access-date=30 January 2017}}</ref>

In the decade preceding the Russian mirror-trading scheme, Deutsche Bank was informed of substantial and widespread compliance concerns. The offsetting trades in this instance lacked economic purpose and could have been used to facilitate money laundering or other illegal activity.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2017 |title=CONSENT ORDER UNDER NEW YORK BANKING LAW §§ 39, 44 and 44-a |url=https://www.dfs.ny.gov/system/files/documents/2020/03/ea170130_deustche_bank.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210819120502/https://www.dfs.ny.gov/system/files/documents/2020/03/ea170130_deustche_bank.pdf |archive-date=19 August 2021 |publisher=NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF FINANCIAL SERVICES}}</ref> On 30 January 2017, the [[New York State Department of Financial Services|NYSDFS (New York State Department of Financial Services)]] fined Deutsche Bank $425&nbsp;million for violating New York's [[Money laundering#Anti-money laundering|anti-money laundering laws]]. There was a "mirror trading" scheme involved. Deutsche Bank's Moscow, London, and New York branches laundered $10&nbsp;billion out of Russia.<ref name=":2" />

The Global Laundromat scandal revealed Deutsche Bank's involvement in a vast money-laundering operation over the period 2010–2014. The operation may have involved as much as $80&nbsp;billion. In 2019, ''The Guardian'' reported that a confidential internal report at Deutsche Bank showed that the bank could face fines, legal action, and even possible prosecution of senior management over the bank's role in the money laundering.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 April 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank faces action over $20bn Russian money-laundering scheme |url=http://www.theguardian.com/business/2019/apr/17/deutsche-bank-faces-action-over-20bn-russian-money-laundering-scheme |access-date=2 March 2022 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref>

In 2020, it was reported that Deutsche Bank was pursuing an expansion of its Russia operations.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Patricia Kowsmann |author2=Jenny Strasburg |date=26 November 2020 |title=Outside Monitors Urge Deutsche Bank to Quit Russia |language=en-US |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/outside-monitors-urge-deutsche-bank-to-quit-russia-11606386601 |access-date=2 March 2022 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref>

In the wake of [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|Russia's 2022 invasion of Ukraine]], Deutsche Bank refused to close down its Russia business. At the same time, other banks and major businesses were exiting Russia.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gilchrist |first=Karen |date=10 March 2022 |title=Deutsche Bank defends decision not to exit Russia: It's not 'practical' right now |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/03/10/deutsche-bank-says-not-practical-to-exit-russia-business.html |access-date=11 March 2022 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref>

In June 2023, the bank notified customers that it could no longer guarantee them access to the shares they hold on the basis of depositary receipts issued prior to February 2022. He explained this by the shortage of shares in the Russian depository. The bank also warned that it would be able to return the funds for the share significantly below the market price.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/deutsche-bank-tells-investors-some-their-russian-shares-are-missing-2023-06-26/|title=Exclusive: Deutsche Bank tells investors some of their Russian shares are missing|date=26 June 2023|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>

=== Relationship with Donald Trump, 1995–2021===
{{anchor|Robert Mueller investigation}}
{{further|Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January–June 2017)|Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July–December 2017)|Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019)|Wealth of Donald Trump}}

Deutsche Bank is widely recognized as being the largest creditor to real-estate mogul and politician [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Enrich |first=David |date=4 February 2020 |title=The Money Behind Trump's Money |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/magazine/deutsche-bank-trump.html |access-date=25 October 2023 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Luke |last2=Makortoff |first2=Kalyeena |date=13 January 2021 |title=Deutsche Bank joins companies cutting ties with Donald Trump |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2021/jan/12/deutsche-bank-severs-ties-with-donald-trump |access-date=25 October 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=12 January 2021 |title=Trump dropped by biggest lender Deutsche Bank for future business: NYT |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-deutsche-bank-idUSKBN29H0PM |access-date=25 October 2023}}</ref> 45th President of the United States, lending him and his company more than $2&nbsp;billion over twenty years ending 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Enrich |first1=David |last2=Protess |first2=Ben |last3=Rashbaum |first3=William K. |last4=Weiser |first4=Benjamin |date=5 August 2020 |title=Trump's Bank Was Subpoenaed by N.Y. Prosecutors in Criminal Inquiry |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/08/05/nyregion/trump-taxes-vance-deutsche-bank.html }}</ref> The bank held more than $360 million in outstanding loans to him prior to his 2016 election. Although his 2019 final report never mentioned Deutsche Bank, as of December 2017, [[Mueller special counsel investigation|Special Counsel Robert Mueller]] investigated Deutsche Bank's role in Trump and Russian parties allegedly cooperating to elect him.<ref name="busin-2018">{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Allan |date=8 December 2017 |title=Trump's long and winding history with Deutsche Bank could now be at the center of Robert Mueller's investigation |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-deutsche-bank-mueller-2017-12 |access-date=29 January 2018 |website=Business Insider}}</ref> {{As of|2019|March}}, Deutsche Bank's relationship with Trump was also under investigation by two [[United States congressional committee|U.S. congressional committees]] and [[New York civil investigation of The Trump Organization|by the New York attorney general]].<ref name="2019-03-18-nyt">{{Cite web |last=Enrich |first=David |author-link=David Enrich |date=18 March 2019 |title=A Mar-a-Lago Weekend and an Act of God: Trump's History With Deutsche Bank |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/18/business/trump-deutsche-bank.html |access-date=19 March 2019 |website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Enrich |first=David |author-link=David Enrich |date=18 March 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank and Trump: $2 Billion in Loans and a Wary Board |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/18/business/deutsche-bank-donald-trump.html |access-date=8 November 2019 }}</ref><ref name="TrakingTrumpInvestigationsNYT">{{Cite news |last1=Buchanan |first1=Larry |last2=Yourish |first2=Karen |date=25 September 2019 |title=Tracking 30 Investigations Related to Trump |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/05/13/us/politics/trump-investigations.html |access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref>

In April 2019, [[United States House of Representatives|House]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] subpoenaed the Bank for Trump's personal and financial records.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Flitter |first1=Emily |last2=Enrich |first2=David |author-link2=David Enrich |date=15 April 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Is Subpoenaed for Trump Records by House Democrats |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/15/business/deutsche-bank-trump-finances-congress.html |access-date=16 April 2019 |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Kara Scannell |author2=Jeremy Herb |date=16 April 2019 |title=House committees issue subpoenas to Deutsche Bank, JP Morgan Chase, Citigroup, Bank of America to probe Trump's finances |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/15/politics/deutsche-bank-subpoena/index.html |access-date=16 April 2019 |website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Zachary Warmbrodt |author2=John Bresnahan |date=15 April 2019 |title=House Democrats subpoena Deutsche Bank in Trump investigation |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/15/democrats-subpoena-deutsche-bank-1277199 |access-date=16 April 2019 |website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hosenball |first1=Mark |author-link=Mark Hosenball |last2=Beech |first2=Eric |last3=Zargham |first3=Mohammad |last4=Osterman |first4=Cynthia |last5=Adler |first5=Leslie |date=15 April 2019 |title=House panels issue subpoenas to Deutsche Bank, others in Trump probe |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-banks-idUSKCN1RR2FW |access-date=16 April 2019 |website=Reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Demijian |first=Karoun |author-link=Karoun Demirjian |date=15 April 2019 |title=House Democrats subpoena Deutsche Bank, other financial institutions tied to Trump |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/house-democrats-subpoena-deutsche-bank-other-financial-institutions-tied-to-trump/2019/04/15/00d0042e-5fee-11e9-9ff2-abc984dc9eec_story.html |access-date=16 April 2019 |newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> On 29 April 2019, U.S. President Donald Trump, his business, and his children [[Donald Trump Jr.]], [[Eric Trump]], and [[Ivanka Trump]] sued Deutsche Bank and [[Capital One]] bank to block them from turning over financial records to congressional committees.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Alesci |first=Cristina |author-link=Cristina Alesci |date=30 April 2019 |title=Trump team sues Deutsche Bank and Capital One to keep them from turning over financial records to Congress |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/29/politics/trump-lawsuit-capital-one/index.html |access-date=30 April 2019 |website=CNN}}</ref> On 22 May 2019, judge [[Edgardo Ramos]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|federal District Court in Manhattan]] rejected the Trump suit against Deutsche Bank, ruling the bank must comply with congressional subpoenas.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Flitter |first1=Emily |last2=McKinley |first2=Jesse |last3=Enrich |first3=David |author-link3=David Enrich |last4=Fandos |first4=Nicholas |date=22 May 2019 |title=Trump's Financial Secrets Move Closer to Disclosure |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/business/deutsche-bank-trump-subpoena.html }}</ref> Six days later, Ramos granted Trump's attorneys their request for a [[Stay of proceedings|stay]] so they could pursue an expedited appeal through the courts.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Merle |first=Renae |date=28 May 2019 |title=House subpoenas for Trump's bank records put on hold while president appeals |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/05/29/house-subpoenas-trumps-bank-records-put-hold-while-president-appeals/ |access-date=8 November 2019 |newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> In October 2019, a federal appeals court said the bank asserted it did not have Trump's tax returns.<ref>{{Cite news |date=11 October 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank tells U.S. court it does not have Trump's tax returns |newspaper=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-tax-deutsche-bank-idUSKBN1WP28E |via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> In December 2019, the [[Second Circuit Court of Appeals]] ruled that Deutsche Bank must release Trump's financial records, with some exceptions, to congressional committees; Trump was given seven days to seek another stay pending a possible appeal to the Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Enrich |first=David |date=3 December 2019 |title=Trump Loses Appeal on Deutsche Bank Subpoenas |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/03/business/trump-deutsche-bank-subpoena.html | work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

In May 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported  that anti-money laundering specialists in the bank detected what appeared to be suspicious transactions involving entities controlled by Trump and his son-in-law [[Jared Kushner]], for which they recommended filing [[suspicious activity report]]s with the [[Financial Crimes Enforcement Network]] of the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]], but bank executives rejected the recommendations. One specialist noted money moving from [[Kushner Companies]] to Russian individuals and flagged it in part because of the bank's previous involvement in a Russian money-laundering scheme.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Enrich |first=David |author-link=David Enrich |date=19 May 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Staff Saw Suspicious Activity in Trump and Kushner Accounts |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/19/business/deutsche-bank-trump-kushner.html |access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Jethro |date=31 January 2017 |title=Deutsche Bank fined for $10 billion Russian money-laundering scheme |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/01/31/investing/deutsche-bank-us-fine-russia-money-laundering/index.html |access-date=8 November 2019 |website=CNN Money}}</ref>

On 19 November 2019, Thomas Bowers, a former Deutsche Bank executive and head of the American wealth management division, was reported to have committed suicide in his Malibu home.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Levai |first1=Eric |last2=Stedman |first2=Scott |date=27 November 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Executive Who Signed Off On Trump Loans Kills Himself At Age 55 |url=https://forensicnews.net/2019/11/27/deutsche-bank-executive-who-signed-off-on-trump-loans-kills-self-at-age-55/ |archive-date=27 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127190450/https://forensicnews.net/2019/11/27/deutsche-bank-executive-who-signed-off-on-trump-loans-kills-self-at-age-55/}}</ref> Bowers had been in charge of overseeing and personally signing over $360 million in high-risk loans for Trump's National Doral Miami resort.<ref>Flitter, Emily; Enrich, David (15 April 2019). "Deutsche Bank Is Subpoenaed for Trump Records by House Democrats". ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 16 April 2019.</ref> The loans had been subject to a criminal investigation by special counsel Robert Mueller in his investigation of the president's 2016 campaign involvement in Russian election meddling. Documents on those loans have also been subpoenaed from Deutsche Bank by the House Democrats together with the financial documents of the president. A relationship between Bowers's responsibilities and apparent suicide has not been established; the Los Angeles County Medical Examiner – Coroner closed the case, giving no indication to wrongdoing by third parties.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Los Angeles County Medical Examiner-Coroner |url=https://mec.lacounty.gov/case-detail/?caseNumber=2019-08698 |archive-date=27 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127183008/https://mec.lacounty.gov/case-detail/?caseNumber=2019-08698}}</ref>

In early 2021, Deutsche Bank elected to discontinue its relationship with Donald Trump following the [[January 6 United States Capitol attack]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Egan |first=Charles Riley and Matt |date=12 January 2021 |title=Deutsche Bank won't do any more business with Trump |website=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/12/investing/deutsche-bank-trump/index.html}}</ref>

=== Fine for business with Jeffrey Epstein, 2020 ===
Deutsche Bank lent money and traded currencies for the well-known sex offender [[Jeffrey Epstein]] up to May 2019, long after Epstein's 2008 guilty plea in Florida to soliciting prostitution from underage girls, according to news reports.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1149116131250266112 |user=davidenrich |title=Exclusive: @DeutscheBank had an extensive relationship with Jeffrey Epstein, lending him money and providing trading services — up until May 2019, when the bank cut him off.https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/10/business/jeffrey-epstein-net-worth.html |author=David Enrich |date=10 July 2019 |access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news |last1=Stewart |first1=James B. |last2=Goldstein |first2=Matthew |last3=Kelly |first3=Kate |last4=Enrich |first4=David |date=10 July 2019 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's 'Infinite Means' May Be a Mirage |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/10/business/jeffrey-epstein-net-worth.html |access-date=11 July 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Metcalf |first1=Tom |last2=Robinson |first2=Matt |date=10 July 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank ended its relationship with Jeffrey Epstein this year |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2019/07/10/deutsche-bank-ended-its-relationship-with-jeffrey-epstein-this-year/ysdWK3tkvmj4XGFpkn1c6O/story.html |access-date=11 July 2019 |website=The Boston Globe |language=en-US}}</ref> Epstein and his businesses had dozens of accounts through the private-banking division.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |last1=Enrich |first1=David |last2=Becker |first2=Jo |date=23 July 2019 |title=Jeffrey Epstein Moved Money Overseas in Transactions His Bank Flagged to U.S. |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/23/business/jeffrey-epstein-deutsche-bank.html |access-date=24 July 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hong |first=Jenny Strasburg and Nicole |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Financial Trail Goes Through Deutsche Bank |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/jeffrey-epsteins-financial-trail-goes-through-deutsche-bank-11563911131 |access-date=24 July 2019 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=23 July 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref> From 2013 to 2018, "Epstein, his related entities and his associates" had opened over forty accounts with Deutsche Bank.<ref name="NYT_20200707" />

According to ''The New York Times'', Deutsche Bank managers overruled compliance officers who raised concerns about Epstein's reputation''.''<ref name=":2" />

The bank found suspicious transactions in which Epstein moved money out of the United States, ''[[The Times]]'' reported.<ref name=":0" />

On 7 July 2020, the New York Department of Financial Services (DFS) imposed a $150&nbsp;million penalty on Deutsche Bank, in connection with Epstein. The bank had "ignored red flags on Epstein".<ref name="NYT_20200707">{{Cite news |last=Goldstein |first=Matthew |date=7 July 2020 |title=Deutsche Bank Settles Over Ignored Red Flags on Jeffrey Epstein |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/07/07/business/jeffrey-epstein-deutsche-bank-settlement.html |access-date=7 July 2020 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="DFS_PR_20200707">{{Cite press release |title=Superintendent Lacewell Announces DFS Imposes $150 Million Penalty on Deutsche Bank in Connection with Bank's Relationship with Jeffrey Epstein and Correspondent Relationships with Danske Estonia And FBME Bank |date=7 July 2020 |url=https://www.dfs.ny.gov/reports_and_publications/press_releases/pr202007071 |access-date=7 July 2020 |work=Department of Financial Services}}</ref> Later that month, the son and husband of the judge involved in the trial were shot by a gunman posing as a FedEx driver, with the son dying of his injuries.<ref>https://fortune.com/2020/07/20/epstein-trial-judges-son-killed-hitman-deutsche-bank-esther-salas/</ref>

On 24 November, two unnamed women that accused Epstein of sexual abuse and sex trafficking also sued Deutsche Bank for its role in enabling Epstein to run his sex-trafficking operations by ignoring red flags regarding his account and the withdrawal of suspiciously high sums of money.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-63750504 | title=Jeffrey Epstein victims sue several major banks | date=25 November 2022 | publisher=BBC News |access-date=25 November 2022}}</ref>

=== Involvement in Danske Bank money-laundering scandal, 2018 ===
On 19 November 2018, a whistleblower of the [[Danske Bank money laundering scandal]] stated that a large European bank was involved in helping Danske process $150&nbsp;billion in suspect funds.<ref name="Reuters2018-11-19">{{Cite news |last1=Jensen |first1=Teis |last2=Gronholt-Pedersen |first2=Jacob |date=19 November 2018 |title=Danske whistleblower says big European bank handled $150 billion in... |language=en-US |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-danske-bank-moneylaundering/danske-whistleblower-says-big-european-bank-handled-150-billion-in-payments-idUSKCN1NO0ZR |access-date=20 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217002110/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-danske-bank-moneylaundering/danske-whistleblower-says-big-european-bank-handled-150-billion-in-payments-idUSKCN1NO0ZR |archive-date=17 December 2018}}</ref> Although the whistleblower, Howard Wilkinson, did not name Deutsche Bank directly, another inside source claimed the institute in question was Deutsche Bank's U.S. unit.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Arons |first1=Steven |last2=Barnert |first2=Jan-Patrick |last3=Comfort |first3=Nicholas |date=20 November 2018 |title=Deutsche Bank Hits Record Low on New Worry Over Danske Role |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-20/deutsche-bank-hits-another-record-low-on-money-laundering-worry?srnd=premium-europe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129162444/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-11-20/deutsche-bank-hits-another-record-low-on-money-laundering-worry |archive-date=29 November 2018 |access-date=20 November 2018 |website=bloomberg.com}}</ref>
In 2020 it became known that the U.S. arm of Deutsche Bank processed more than $150&nbsp;billion of the $230&nbsp;billion dirty money through New York, for which it was fined 150 million $. After a raid in 2019, Frankfurt-based prosecutors imposed a fine of $15.8&nbsp;million in 2020 for DB's failure on more than 600 occasions to promptly report suspicious transactions.<ref name="icij">{{Cite news |last=Simon Bowers |date=16 October 2020 |title=German prosecutors drop probe into Deutsche Bank ties to Estonian dirty money scandal – ICIJ |language=en-US |url=https://www.icij.org/investigations/fincen-files/german-prosecutors-drop-probe-into-deutsche-bank-ties-to-estonian-dirty-money-scandal/ |access-date=13 October 2021}}</ref>

===Improper handling of ADRs, 2018===

On 20 July 2018, Deutsche Bank agreed to pay nearly $75&nbsp;million to settle charges of improper handling of "pre-released" [[American depositary receipt]] (ADRs) under investigation of the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC). Deutsche Bank didn't admit or deny the investigation findings but agreed to pay disgorgement of more than $44.4&nbsp;million in ill-gotten gains plus $6.6&nbsp;million in prejudgment interest and a penalty of $22.2&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=SEC.gov {{!}} Deutsche Bank to Pay Nearly $75 Million for Improper Handling of ADRs |url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2018-138 |access-date=8 March 2019 |website=sec.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=20 July 2018 |title=Deutsche to pay $75 million to settle ADRs abuses case, U.S. SEC says |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-sec-idUSKBN1KA274 |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref>

=== Malaysian 1MDB fund ===
In July 2019, U.S. prosecutors investigated Deutsche Bank's role in a multibillion-dollar fraud scandal involving the [[1Malaysia Development Berhad]], or 1MDB.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Aruna Viswanatha |author2=Bradley Hope |author3=Jenny Strasburg |title=U.S. Investigating Deutsche Bank's Dealings With Malaysian Fund 1MDB |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-investigating-deutsche-bank-s-dealings-with-malaysian-fund-1mdb-11562798907 |access-date=11 July 2019 |website=The Wall Street Journal |date=10 July 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="NYTMalaysia">{{Cite news |last=Flitter |first=Emily |date=10 July 2019 |title=Deutsche Bank Caught Up in Scandal Over Malaysian 1MDB Fund |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/10/business/deutsche-bank-1mdb-malaysia.html |access-date=11 July 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Deutsche Bank helped raise $1.2&nbsp;billion for the 1MDB in 2014.<ref name="NYTMalaysia" /> As of May 2021 Malaysia sued Deutsche Bank to recover billions in alleged losses from a corruption scandal at the fund.<ref>{{Cite news |date=10 May 2021 |title=Malaysia sues Deutsche Bank, JP Morgan, Coutts over 1MDB |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/malaysia-sues-deutsche-bank-jp-morgan-coutts-over-1mdb-2021-05-10/ |access-date=13 October 2021}}</ref>

=== Commodities trading, bribery fine, 2021 ===
In January 2021, Deutsche Bank agreed to pay a U.S. fine of more than $130&nbsp;million for a scheme to conceal bribes to foreign officials in countries such as [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[China]], and the city of [[Abu Dhabi]], between 2008 and 2017 and a commodities case where it [[Spoofing (finance)|spoofed]] precious metals futures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wolf|first=Brett|date=13 January 2021|title=Deutsche Bank reaches $130 million settlement over U.S. bribery, commodities|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/bc-finreg-deutsche-bribery-settlement-idUSKBN29I2VF|access-date=24 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=8 January 2021|title=Deutsche Bank Agrees to Pay over $130 Million to Resolve Foreign Corrupt Practices Act and Fraud Case|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/deutsche-bank-agrees-pay-over-130-million-resolve-foreign-corrupt-practices-act-and-fraud|access-date=24 February 2021|website=www.justice.gov|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Welle (www.dw.com) |first=Deutsche Welle |date= 8 January 2021 |title=Deutsche Bank handed $124 million in bribery fines by US court |url=https://www.dw.com/en/deutsche-bank-handed-124-million-in-bribery-fines-by-us-court/a-56176485 |access-date=24 February 2021 |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB}}</ref>

=== Greenwashing, 2022 ===
On the 31st of May, 2022, police in Germany raided the offices of Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt over allegations of greenwashing.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank, DWS Raided Over Allegations of Greenwashing |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-05-31/deutsche-bank-s-dws-unit-raided-amid-allegations-of-greenwashing}}</ref> In late July 2023, the Financial Times reported that DWS (80% owned by Deustche Bank) which was also involved in the case was nearing a settlement having earmarked €21mn for the settlement and incurred €39mn in legal costs. <ref>{{Cite web |title=DWS closes in on settlement over greenwashing scandal |url=https://www.ft.com/content/38be4231-21cf-46e3-8b6a-88a4e923f01c }}</ref> DWS had made misleading statements about the size of their ESG assets and the employee who raised concerns was fired unfairly. Reuters composed a more extensive timeline highlighting how the issue developed over the course of several years including when the stock price fell sharply on news of a US SEC investigation and the resignation of the CEO.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Deutsche Bank's DWS and allegations of 'greenwashing' |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/deutsche-banks-dws-allegations-greenwashing-2022-06-09/}}</ref>

== Leadership ==
{{Chief executives of Deutsche Bank}}
After Deutsche Bank was first organized in 1870, the Management Board was represented by a Speaker ({{lang-de|Vorstandssprecher}}). Beginning in February 2012, the bank has been led by two co-CEOs; in July 2015 it announced it would be led by one CEO beginning in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deutsche Bank Annual Report |url=https://annualreport.deutsche-bank.com/2012/ar/deutschebankgroup/corporateprofile/managementstructure.html |access-date=19 November 2015 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023637/https://annualreport.deutsche-bank.com/2012/ar/deutschebankgroup/corporateprofile/managementstructure.html }}</ref>

